;a:5:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Marketing\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:15:\"email marketing\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:7:\"WPForms\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:17:\"list segmentation\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"email campaign\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:29:\"https://wpforms.com/?p=300219\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:627:\"<p>Are you wondering how to make the most of your institutionâs recruiting emails? Learning how to convince students to open recruitment emails goes beyond basic email marketing skills. After all, students have an overwhelming number of options when they graduate high school and getting them to agree to consider your university can be tough. In [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/proven-ways-to-convince-students-to-open-recruitment-emails/\">4 Proven Ways to Convince Students to Open Recruitment Emails</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"Lindsay Liedke\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:12324:\"<p>Are you wondering how to make the most of your institutionâs recruiting emails? Learning how to convince students to open recruitment emails goes beyond <a href=\"http://optinmonster.com/beginners-guide-to-email-marketing/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">basic email marketing skills</a>. After all, students have an overwhelming number of options when they graduate high school and getting them to agree to consider your university can be tough.</p>\n<p>In this article, weâll share some proven ways to convince students to open recruitment emails so you can establish your school as a top choice amongst prospective students.</p>\n<p>So, letâs get started.</p>\n<h3>1. Use a Powerful Online WordPress Form Builder</h3>\n<p>The first step to getting people to open your recruitment email campaigns is to capture email addresses of those that might be interested in attending your school. After all, without an email list you canât send out emails, drive traffic to your site, and encourage people to apply to your school.</p>\n<p>And since <a href=\"https://beamery.com/academy/state-of-talent-acquisition-2017\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">85% of recruiters rely on email</a> to contact potential students and build relationships with them, itâs important you use a good online form solution to capture peopleâs email addresses.</p>\n<p>Luckily, <a href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a> is perfect for doing just that. In fact, WPForms is the <strong>most beginner friendly WordPress form builder plugin</strong> on the market to date. It requires zero coding skills, comes with over a hundred pre-designed templates to get you started, and is simple to add anywhere on your website.</p>\n<p>If you need to capture email addresses so you can launch your recruitment campaigns, start with WPFormsâ simple contact form template.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-218831\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Simple-Contact-Form.png\" alt=\"Simple Contact Form\" width=\"562\" height=\"372\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Simple-Contact-Form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Simple-Contact-Form-300x199.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>From there, you can add and delete any form fields you want to customize it to meet your needs.</p>\n<p>That said, if your aim is to get people to subscribe so they can learn more about your school, see what it has to offer, and potentially apply, you might want to add some of these form fields in addition to the default Name, Email, and Comment or Message on our <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-simple-contact-form-in-wordpress/\">simple contact form</a>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Dropdown, Checkboxes, or Multiple Choice options so people can choose what major theyâre interested in receiving information about</li>\n<li>A <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-add-a-gdpr-agreement-field-to-your-sites-forms/\">GDPR Agreement</a> field so people can agree to receiving marketing materials from you</li>\n<li>Phone and Date / Time fields so you can have a representative reach out at a convenient time to discuss options</li>\n<li>An Address field so you can mail additional information for those interested in learning more</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Take a look at how <a href=\"https://www.etoncollege.ca/admissions/contact-admissions-team\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Eton College</a> adds form fields to their Request More Info form to help narrow down the type of information people want:</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-300222\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-field-example.png\" alt=\"form field example\" width=\"562\" height=\"591\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-field-example.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-field-example-285x300.png 285w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>The great thing about WPForms is that it integrates with the following email service providers:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/mailchimp-addon/\">MailChimp</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/aweber-addon/\">AWeber</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/getresponse-addon/\">GetResponse</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/features/constant-contact/\">Constant Contact</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/campaign-monitor-addon/\">Campaign Monitor</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/drip-addon/\">Drip</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Creating a highly converting contact form is the first step to convincing students to open your recruiting emails.</p>\n<h3>2. Segment Your Subscribers</h3>\n<p>Thereâs no sense sending out generic recruitment emails to all of your subscribers if your goal is to get students to open them. After all, potential students will be interested in receiving different information to suit their individual needs.</p>\n<p>Thatâs why segmenting your email lists is so helpful. In fact, <a href=\"https://mailchimp.com/resources/effects-of-list-segmentation-on-email-marketing-stats/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">MailChimp claims</a> that segmented email lists result in 14.31% more email opens and 100.95% more clicks than non-segmented lists.</p>\n<p>See how MailChimp lets you create different email lists:</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-300224\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/segment-list-example.png\" alt=\"segment list example\" width=\"562\" height=\"633\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/segment-list-example.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/segment-list-example-266x300.png 266w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>If you arenât sure where to begin when it comes to segmenting your subscribers, check out these ideas:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Stage in the Enrollment Process:</strong> New prospects and those that have opened recruitment emails before will need different email campaigns.</li>\n<li><strong>Location:</strong> international students will need different information about enrollment than local students. Even out-of-state students will have a different application process and tuition costs. If you want to learn about subscribersâ locations when they sign up, all you have to do is use the WPFormsâ <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/geolocation-addon/\">Geolocation addon</a>.</li>\n<li><strong>Interests:</strong> as we mentioned above, finding out what interests potential students, and using that data to create email campaigns, is much more effective than a general information email blast.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Segmenting your email lists and sending out campaigns based on those lists will result in higher open and clickthrough rates. And who knows, you might even have a higher student enrollment for the year.</p>\n<h3>3. Focus on the Email Subject Line</h3>\n<p>If you can get students to subscribe to your newsletter or request more information, <strong>youâve won half the battle</strong>. But getting them to actually open your emails can be tricky.</p>\n<p>But not if you focus on the email subject line.</p>\n<p>Here are some ways you can grab peopleâs attention from the start and get them to open your emails:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Create a sense of urgency by adding important dates or deadlines. For instance, âHurry, Apply Before the 15th to Guarantee Enrollmentâ</li>\n<li>Use the power of numbers to grab a studentâs attention. For example, â5 Reasons Why Getting Your Degree at X University Rocksâ</li>\n<li>Ask a question that will compel someone to open an email to find the answer. Try something like âHave You Heard About Our New Study Abroad Program?â</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/email-personalization-examples/\">Personalize the subject line</a> using the studentâs name. This will draw attention and build a better relationship. For example, try âHey Lindsay, Learn About Why You Should Attend U of E!â</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Of course, these are just some examples of how you can stand out from the competition.</p>\n<p>If you want to make sure your email subject is amazing, check out the <a href=\"https://coschedule.com/email-subject-line-tester?utm_campaign=email-subject-line-tester-launch&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_source=autopilot&amp;utm_term=free-email-subject-line-tester&amp;utm_content=eslt-2\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">CoSchedule Email Analyzer</a> and see for yourself:</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-300221\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/coschedule-email-headline-analyzer.png\" alt=\"coschedule email headline analyzer\" width=\"562\" height=\"419\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/coschedule-email-headline-analyzer.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/coschedule-email-headline-analyzer-300x224.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>A score of 40 above is what you should aim for so your campaigns get the most opens.</p>\n<p>Also, donât forget to experiment with emojis, subject line length, and <a href=\"https://optinmonster.com/700-power-words-that-will-boost-your-conversions/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"> power words</a> to boost opens and clickthroughs.</p>\n<h3>4. Watch Your Timing</h3>\n<p>Prospective students may sign up to receive information from a ton of potential schools they want to attend.</p>\n<p>If you donât want to become a forgotten option, send out your first recruitment campaign within 24 hours of someone subscribing. This way theyâll remember subscribing and any information that drew them to your institution in the first place.</p>\n<p>For example, within minutes of requesting additional information from the <a href=\"https://www.phoenix.edu/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">University of Phoenix</a>, an email was delivered:</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-300223\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/request-for-info-example.png\" alt=\"request for info example\" width=\"562\" height=\"601\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/request-for-info-example.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/request-for-info-example-281x300.png 281w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Here are some of the highlights of this email encouraging people to open and engage with the email:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The from name and email subject line is clear, though not that exciting, which reminds the subscriber they requested more information</li>\n<li>There are clickable links to the schoolâs homepage, programs, tuition information, credit transfer information, and even social media profiles</li>\n<li>Thereâs a phone number to call for those that prefer to talk to someone</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Sending emails right away shows students they are a priority and that you have lots to offer.</p>\n<p>And there you have it! Some of the best ways to cater to and convince students to open recruitment emails.</p>\n<p>If you want to make things even easier on students that not only open and engage with your recruitment emails, but actually want to apply to your institution, make sure to check out <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-require-payment-on-a-wordpress-file-upload-form/\">how to require payment on a WordPress file upload form</a>.</p>\n<p>This tutorial will help you add payment fields to the College Application template that is available in the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/features/form-templates/\">Form Templates Pack addon</a> and is perfect for accepting college application fees from students directly through your form.</p>\n<p>So, what are you waiting for? Get started with the most powerful <a href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WordPress forms plugin</a> today.</p>\n<p>And donât forget, if you like this article, then please follow us on <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/wpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> and <a href=\"http://twitter.com/easywpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/proven-ways-to-convince-students-to-open-recruitment-emails/\">4 Proven Ways to Convince Students to Open Recruitment Emails</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:85:\"https://wpforms.com/proven-ways-to-convince-students-to-open-recruitment-emails/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:1;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:51:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:43:\"WPForms vs Wufoo: Which is the Best Choice?\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:62:\"https://wpforms.com/wpforms-vs-wufoo-which-is-the-best-choice/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:70:\"https://wpforms.com/wpforms-vs-wufoo-which-is-the-best-choice/#respond\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Wed, 24 Oct 2018 12:00:14 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:4:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Marketing\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:12:\"contact form\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:7:\"WPForms\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:12:\"form builder\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:29:\"https://wpforms.com/?p=299286\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:552:\"<p>Are looking for a Wufoo alternative? If youâre trying to decide which form builder to use on your website, you might be curious to know how WPForms matches up against Wufoo. In this article, weâll compare WPForms and Wufoo so you can decide which is the best form plugin for you. The 5 criteria weâll [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/wpforms-vs-wufoo-which-is-the-best-choice/\">WPForms vs Wufoo: Which is the Best Choice?</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"Lindsay Liedke\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:20888:\"<p>Are looking for a Wufoo alternative? If youâre trying to decide which form builder to use on your website, you might be curious to know how WPForms matches up against Wufoo.</p>\n<p>In this article, weâll compare WPForms and Wufoo so you can decide which is the best form plugin for you.</p>\n<p>The 5 criteria weâll use in our WPForms vs Wufoo showdown will be:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Ease of Use</li>\n<li>Features</li>\n<li>Support</li>\n<li>Account Management</li>\n<li>Price</li>\n</ul>\n<p>So, letâs take a look at the comparison of WPForms vs Wufoo to see which choice is better suited for your business needs.</p>\n<h3>Ease of Use</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.wufoo.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Wufoo</a> is an online form builder that comes with a drag &amp; drop interface that requires no coding.</p>\n<p>Adding fields to your forms is easy to do. All you have to do is drag the field of your choice from the list of choices to the form youâre creating. You can also use one of their pre-made templates to get you started.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-299307\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/wufoo-drag-drop-form-example.png\" alt=\"wufoo drag &amp; drop form example\" width=\"562\" height=\"423\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/wufoo-drag-drop-form-example.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/wufoo-drag-drop-form-example-300x226.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>To make changes to the form fields, click on the field you want to customize, and the Field Settings will appear. You can also customize your form by applying themes. This gives you a chance to globally change specific elements on your form such as:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Logo</li>\n<li>Typography</li>\n<li>Backgrounds</li>\n<li>Borders</li>\n<li>Shadows</li>\n<li>Buttons</li>\n</ul>\n<p>You can also apply custom CSS to your forms if you know what youâre doing.</p>\n<p>Although initially all of this customization seems great, the problem is, once you start diving in <strong>thereâs a lot to it</strong>.</p>\n<p>And while Wufoo claims you can have a form up and running within seconds, the truth is, if you get into all the theme applications, youâll have to spend a lot of time customizing every single element if you want things to match.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-299311\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/wufoo-theme-designer-example.png\" alt=\"wufoo theme designer example\" width=\"562\" height=\"470\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/wufoo-theme-designer-example.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/wufoo-theme-designer-example-300x251.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Itâs easy to become overwhelmed with all the design choices Wufoo has available for its forms, which can end up hurting your brand more than help it.</p>\n<p>After all, simplicity is usually best.</p>\n<p>When you embed a form onto your website, the background, header, and border styling is all stripped to make sure it integrates onto your website perfectly. And just think, you just spent all that time customizing your forms and applying themes.</p>\n<p>The only way to get those elements to show on your website is to apply them directly using HTML or CSS, which not everyone knows how to do. That hardly seems easy to use if you ask us.</p>\n<p>Lastly, when you make changes to the theme of your form, the only way you can see the changes is to click the View Form button, which makes visualizing the end result difficult.</p>\n<p>On the other hand, WPForms is a modern WordPress form builder that <strong>focuses on usability and simplicity</strong>.</p>\n<p>In fact, itâs the most beginner friendly WordPress contact form plugin on the market today, and truly requires no coding knowledge to create forms.</p>\n<p>WPForms comes with pre-designed templates that have all the form fields you need to get your form started. And while Wufoo has more templates to choose from, there are not easily found once in your account.</p>\n<p>Accessing WPFormsâ pre-made templates is easy since they are found right in the WPForms Form Editor.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-299348\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/wpforms-templates.png\" alt=\"wpforms templates\" width=\"562\" height=\"514\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/wpforms-templates.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/wpforms-templates-300x274.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>When you want to add a new field to your form, use the drag &amp; drop functionality. Then, click on the field to make changes. As you make changes to your fields, youâll see those changes in real-time on your form in the preview panel.</p>\n<p>WPForms comes with plenty of form fields right out of the box.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-218831\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Simple-Contact-Form.png\" alt=\"Simple Contact Form\" width=\"562\" height=\"372\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Simple-Contact-Form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Simple-Contact-Form-300x199.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>For example, WPForms allows you to <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-simple-order-form-in-wordpress/\">accept payments from site visitors</a> on your forms using <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/stripe-addon/\">Stripe</a>, which supports recurring payments, or <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/paypal-standard-addon/\">PayPal</a>. Plus, it comes with Single Item, Multiple Item, Dropdown Items, Credit Card, and Total form fields so you can <a href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/make-money-online/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">make money online</a> in the easiest way possible.</p>\n<p>And to top it off, WPForms makes <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-add-image-choices-to-fields/\">adding image choices to your forms</a> really simple. This is great if youâre <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-t-shirt-order-form-in-wordpress-step-by-step/\">creating a T-shirt order form</a> and want customers to see what theyâre buying before they pay.</p>\n<p>If you want a form builder plugin thatâs easy to use right out of the box, but still offers a ton of built-in features, WPForms works great as an alternative to Wufoo.</p>\n<p><strong>Winner: WPForms</strong></p>\n<h3>Features</h3>\n<p>Wufoo does offer users a fairly quick solution to setting up a basic contact form if you donât want to get into theme styling or code customizations.</p>\n<p>That said, their features are somewhat limited when compared to WPForms.</p>\n<p>Letâs take a look at Wufoo offers customers:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Form Fields:</strong> in addition to standard form fields like Name, Email, Phone, and Address, Wufoo has stand out field like Dropdown and Multiple Choice, Page Break, Rating, Time, Likert, and File Upload. But thatâs it; there are no other specialty fields.</li>\n<li><strong>Payments:</strong> Wufoo does allow site visitors to submit payments on their forms and has tons of payment gateways to choose from.</li>\n<li><strong>Analytics:</strong> you can only track your metrics using Google Analytics on the two highest priced premium plans. However, there is a section in your account that will allow you to access form metrics such as pageviews, entries, conversion rate, error score, and the average time it takes to complete your forms.</li>\n<li><strong>Notifications and Confirmation Emails:</strong> you can set up email notifications when someone submits a form on your site, and email confirmations to let people know their form has been submitted.</li>\n<li><strong>Smart Logic:</strong> Wufoo has what they call the Rule Builder, which allows you to set up conditional rules to redirect people once they submit a form on your site, hide or show fields based on user behavior, and skip pages based on user behavior.</li>\n<li><strong>File Storage:</strong> there are maximum file storage limits on all Wufoo plans. This includes all the files that are uploaded to your forms by site visitors.</li>\n<li><strong>Form, Entry, and Field Limits:</strong> each Wufoo plan has limits when it comes to the number of forms you can create, entries you can accept, and fields you can add to each form on your site.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Lastly, Wufoo has form sharing functionality that lets you share a link to your form in social media or email campaigns and/or embed forms directly onto your website.</p>\n<p>On the other hand, WPForms stands out as more than just a simple form builder because of the sheer amount of built-in features and addons you receive as a customer:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-clutter-free-forms-with-smart-logic/\">Smart conditional logic</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-save-your-contact-form-data-in-wordpress-database/\">Entry Management</a> from the WordPress dashboard</li>\n<li>Unlimited <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-wordpress-contact-form-multiple-file-upload/\">file upload</a> functionality</li>\n<li>Automatic form confirmations (message, redirect, URL)</li>\n<li>File storage based on your WordPress host, not WPForms</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/surveys-and-polls-addon/\">Survey and poll</a> form creation</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/form-abandonment-addon/\">Partial form saving</a> to capture more leads</li>\n<li>Exhaustive <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-build-spam-free-wordpress-contact-forms-the-ultimate-guide/\">spam protection</a></li>\n<li>Unlimited form, entry, and field limits</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/signature-addon/\">Online signature</a> capability</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/form-locker-addon/\">Form permissions and access controls</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/geolocation-addon/\">Geolocation tracking</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Another neat feature WPForms comes with is its ability to <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/zapier-addon/\">integrate with Zapier</a> and connect your site with over 500 different apps, making management of your site and business a breeze.</p>\n<p>Plus, WPForms seamlessly <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-use-google-analytics-to-track-form-submissions-in-wordpress/\">integrates with Google Analytics</a> using the <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">MonsterInsights plugin</a>, the best Google Analytics plugin on the market, so you always know how well your forms are performing.</p>\n<p>With MonsterInsights, check out the number of impressions and conversions your form receives, as well as an overall conversion rate <strong>right in your WordPress dashboard</strong> to make sure site visitors are filling them out.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-299302\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/monsterinsights-forms-report.png\" alt=\"monsterinsights forms report\" width=\"562\" height=\"317\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/monsterinsights-forms-report.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/monsterinsights-forms-report-300x169.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>If youâre looking for reasons why WPForms might server as a better solution than Wufoo, its feature set alone is compelling. In fact, WPFormsâ flexibility gives you a chance to create <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/research-based-tips-to-improve-contact-form-conversions/\">standout forms that will convert</a>.</p>\n<p><strong>Winner: WPForms</strong></p>\n<h3>Support</h3>\n<p>With Wufoo, you can access support in two ways:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Using the generic contact form and choosing a topic that closely relates to your issue</li>\n<li>Reading articles in the Help Center</li>\n</ol>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-299309\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/wufoo-help-center-support.png\" alt=\"wufoo help center support\" width=\"562\" height=\"459\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/wufoo-help-center-support.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/wufoo-help-center-support-300x245.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>If youâre looking for more comprehensive support through a variety of channels, look no further than the best Wufoo alternative around: WPForms.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-299305\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/wpforms-support.png\" alt=\"wpforms support\" width=\"562\" height=\"456\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/wpforms-support.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/wpforms-support-300x243.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>You can access the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/contact/\">support ticket system</a> and receive help from the knowledgeable and friendly support team, read through the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/\">extensive documentation</a> for configuring every little setting possible, and even <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/blog/\">check out the blog</a> to learn tips and tricks for creating highly converting, good looking WordPress forms.</p>\n<p>And if you want, you can even check out the <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/support/plugin/wpforms-lite\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">official WordPress Repository</a> where people using WPForms Lite get answers to their most pressing questions.</p>\n<p><strong>Winner: WPForms</strong></p>\n<h3>Account Management</h3>\n<p>There is a glaring difference between the way you manage Wufoo forms and WPForms forms: the location.</p>\n<p>With Wufoo, you create an account where you create, save, and manage the forms you build.</p>\n<p>Here, you manage things like:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Saved forms</li>\n<li>Payment integrations</li>\n<li>Share links and embed shortcodes</li>\n<li>Form entries</li>\n</ul>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-299308\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/wufoo-form-management.png\" alt=\"wufoo form management\" width=\"562\" height=\"226\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/wufoo-form-management.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/wufoo-form-management-300x121.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>You can also delete and duplicate forms, add password protection, get API information, and make your forms private in the Wufoo Form Manager.</p>\n<p>Wufoo also has the following tabs in your account:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Report Manager</strong> for accessing form metrics</li>\n<li><strong>Theme Designer</strong> for making global design changes to your forms</li>\n<li><strong>User Management</strong> for those with plans that allow multiple users</li>\n<li><strong>Plans &amp; Pricing</strong> in case you want to compare features and make an upgrade</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Thereâs also an Account section for managing your account, upgrading, and accessing help.</p>\n<p>On the other hand, WPForms lets you manage your forms all within the WordPress dashboard so you never have to leave your website.</p>\n<p>For example, you can do the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>View forms youâve already created</li>\n<li>Create new forms</li>\n<li>Access form entries</li>\n<li>Configure settings related to: your license, email, reCAPTCHA, validation messages, payments, integrations, and more</li>\n<li>Use the import and export tools</li>\n<li>Activate addons that can be used on your forms immediately</li>\n</ul>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-299303\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/wpforms-form-management.png\" alt=\"wpforms form management\" width=\"562\" height=\"277\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/wpforms-form-management.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/wpforms-form-management-300x148.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Managing your websiteâs forms shouldnât be difficult. Fortunately, despite the differences in location, each of these form builders make account management a cinch.</p>\n<p><strong>Winner: Tie</strong></p>\n<h3>Price</h3>\n<p>Both <a href=\"https://www.wufoo.com/pricing/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Wufoo</a> and <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/wpforms-lite/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">WPForms</a> offer free plans for those just getting started.</p>\n<p>That said, weâre going to focus on the premium plans available. After all, thatâs where all the best features are.</p>\n<p>Wufoo has 4 premium plans to choose from ranging from $14.08/month to $183.25/month. Each plan has their own form, entry, user, and upload storage limits. In addition, the more you pay, the more features you unlock.</p>\n<p>For instance, you can access Google Analytics tracking, field encryption, and password protection if you use the Professional plan or higher.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-299310\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/wufoo-price-plans.png\" alt=\"wufoo price plans\" width=\"562\" height=\"314\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/wufoo-price-plans.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/wufoo-price-plans-300x168.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Keep in mind, Wufoo will charge you $0.05 USD for every entry you accept on your website over your planâs limit. There is also no money-back guarantee, as outlined in Wufooâs terms of service, so if you donât like what youâve paid for youâre out of luck.</p>\n<p>On the other hand, WPForms comes in at significantly lower price points, ranging from $39.50/year for the Basic plan to $299.50/year for the Elite plan.</p>\n<p>If you upgrade to a more expensive plan, which still pales in comparison to Wufoo, you can access more <a href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/showcase/best-email-marketing-services/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">email service provider</a> integrations, addons, and priority support. In addition, you can use WPForms on more than one website when you use the Plus plan or higher.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-299304\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/wpforms-price-plans.png\" alt=\"wpforms price plans\" width=\"562\" height=\"467\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/wpforms-price-plans.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/wpforms-price-plans-300x249.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>WPForms offers a 14-day 100% money-back guarantee on all premium plans, so if you change your mind for whatever reason, youâll get your money back. Adding to that, WPForms sticks by the motto âSimple Prices. No Surprises.â</p>\n<p><strong>Winner: WPForms</strong></p>\n<h3>Conclusion:</h3>\n<p>Wufoo seems to offer website owners an easy way to create customized forms for site visitors to fill out. However, upon taking a closer look, weâve come to realize that there is a lot more to this simple contact form builder than meets the eye.</p>\n<p>Itâs much pricier than one would expect, is not as easy and code-free as we initially thought, and doesnât have nearly as many features as you would want for the price youâre paying. Not to mention, the limits placed on form creations, entries, and file upload storage is enough to make you look for a Wufoo alternative immediately.</p>\n<p>On the other hand, WPForms continues to grow in popularity, now with over 10 million downloads, because it offers businesses a faster, easier way to create online forms that go beyond the basics. In fact, price points, feature sets, ease of use, and superior support are all reasons why the most successful business owners choose WPForms as their WordPress form builder solution.</p>\n<p>And there you have it! A comparison of WPForms vs Wufoo, with <strong>WPForms coming out at the clear winner</strong>.</p>\n<p>If youâre still on the fence about whether WPForms is the very best Wufoo alternative, make sure to <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/user-reviews/\">see what our happy customers have to say</a>.</p>\n<p>So, what are you waiting for? Get started with the most powerful <a href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WordPress forms plugin</a> today.</p>\n<p>And donât forget, if you like this article, then please follow us on <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/wpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> and <a href=\"http://twitter.com/easywpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/wpforms-vs-wufoo-which-is-the-best-choice/\">WPForms vs Wufoo: Which is the Best Choice?</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:67:\"https://wpforms.com/wpforms-vs-wufoo-which-is-the-best-choice/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:2;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:57:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:55:\"How to Redirect Users after a WordPress Form Submission\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:72:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-redirect-users-after-a-wordpress-form-submit/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:81:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-redirect-users-after-a-wordpress-form-submit/#comments\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Tue, 23 Oct 2018 12:00:45 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:6:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:19:\"WordPress Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:17:\"form confirmation\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:8:\"redirect\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:3:\"url\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"thank you\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:5;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:11:\"smart logic\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:27:\"https://wpforms.com/?p=5736\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:584:\"<p>Do you want to redirect users to another page after they successfully submit a contact form? Perhaps you want to send them to a thank you page or a custom landing page? In this article, weâll show you how to redirect users after a WordPress form submission. WordPress Form Redirection After Submission After a user [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-redirect-users-after-a-wordpress-form-submit/\">How to Redirect Users after a WordPress Form Submission</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"Lindsay Liedke\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:12031:\"<p>Do you want to redirect users to another page after they successfully submit a contact form? Perhaps you want to send them to a thank you page or a custom landing page?</p>\n<p>In this article, weâll show you how to redirect users after a WordPress form submission.</p>\n<h3>WordPress Form Redirection After Submission</h3>\n<p>After a user submits a form, it can be disorienting for them if they just sit on the same page with no indication of whether their message was received or their form was processed. You can use this opportunity to connect further with your interested visitors and provide a better user experience.</p>\n<p>Here are some of the most common places you can redirect site visitors to after a form submission:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Thank You Page:</strong> send users submitting your contact form to a customized thank you page.</li>\n<li><strong>Hidden Content:</strong> place your <a href=\"http://optinmonster.com/9-lead-magnets-to-increase-subscribers/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">lead magnet</a> on a custom thank you page and make it accessible only to subscribers.</li>\n<li><strong>Schedule Appointments:</strong> if a user submits a <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-request-a-quote-form-in-wordpress/\">request for quote form</a>, you can prompt them to visit your appointment scheduling system and book a time to meet with you.</li>\n<li><strong>Anywhere:</strong> with WPForms, you can redirect users after they submit a form to any page on your website or anywhere online.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Now letâs take a look at how to redirect users after they submit forms on your website.</p>\n<h3>Install and Activate WPForms</h3>\n<p>The first thing youâll need to do is install and activate the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/pricing/\">WPForms plugin</a>. For more details, see this step by step guide on <a title=\"Step by step guide on How to Install a WordPress Plugin\" href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/step-by-step-guide-to-install-a-wordpress-plugin-for-beginners/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">how to install a plugin in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>Once youâve activated the plugin, youâll need to create a new form. If you haven&#8217;t created a form yet, see our step by step guide on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-contact-form-in-wordpress/\">how to create a simple contact form</a>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-218831\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Simple-Contact-Form.png\" alt=\"Simple Contact Form\" width=\"562\" height=\"372\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Simple-Contact-Form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Simple-Contact-Form-300x199.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Keep in mind, you can create any kind of WordPress form using WPForms, especially if you use the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/features/form-templates/\">Form Templates Pack addon</a>, which comes with over 100 different form templates for you to choose from.</p>\n<p>For instance, you can create a:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/create-a-survey-form-in-wordpress-step-by-step/\">Survey form</a> for getting customer feedback</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-an-rsvp-form-in-wordpress/\">RSVP form</a> for streamlining event management</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-set-up-a-volunteer-application-form-in-wordpress/\">Volunteer application form</a> so your organizationâs event is fully staffed</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-simple-order-form-in-wordpress/\">Simple order form</a> for <a href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/make-money-online/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">making money online</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-support-ticket-form-template-best-practices/\">Support ticket form</a> so your customers always have a helping hand</li>\n<li>And so much more</li>\n</ul>\n<p>After youâve created a custom form on your website, click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Redirect Users after a WordPress Form Submission</h3>\n<p>After youâve created your form, youâre ready to redirect users to another page once they submit the form.</p>\n<p>You can redirect your site visitors to two places using WPForms:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>To another page on your website, such as a thank you page</li>\n<li>To an external webpage, such as another website</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Letâs take a look at both options.</p>\n<p><strong>Option 1: Redirect Users to a Page on Your Website</strong><br />\nThe first option is to send users to a specific page within your website.</p>\n<p>You can do this by going to <strong>Settings Â» Confirmation</strong>.</p>\n<p>On the right preview panel, select <strong>Confirmation Type</strong> and then <strong>Show Page</strong> from the dropdown menu.</p>\n<p>After this, click on the <strong>Confirmation Page</strong> dropdown and choose which page you want to send the user to thatâs on your website.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-298457\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/show-page-confirmation.png\" alt=\"show page confirmation\" width=\"562\" height=\"344\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/show-page-confirmation.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/show-page-confirmation-300x184.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<div class=\"alert alert-info\">Note: Before you can successfully redirect users to another page on your website after they submit a form, youâll have to have the page already created on your website so you can choose it from the dropdown menu in the Confirmation settings.</p>\n<p>For help with creating effective thank you pages, check out this roundup of <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/4-thank-you-page-examples-to-boost-customer-loyalty/\">thank you page examples</a> to help boost customer loyalty.</div>\n<p>After you&#8217;ve chosen the page to redirect users to, click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<p><strong>Option 2: Redirect Users to a Page on Another Website</strong><br />\nIf you want, you can redirect site visitors that submit forms on your website to an entirely different website besides your own.</p>\n<p>To do this, go to <strong>Settings Â» Confirmation</strong> and select the <strong>Confirmation Type</strong> as <strong>Go to URL (Redirect)</strong>.</p>\n<p>Then, paste the complete website address you&#8217;d like to send the user to in the section labeled <strong>Confirmation Redirect URL</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-298458\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/wordpress-form-redirect-after-form-submission.png\" alt=\"wordpress form redirect after form submission\" width=\"562\" height=\"330\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/wordpress-form-redirect-after-form-submission.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/wordpress-form-redirect-after-form-submission-300x176.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>After you have configured where to redirect users after they submit a form on your site, click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<p>If you want, you can also set up more than one form redirect based on your site visitorâs behavior when they fill out your forms. For instance, you might redirect one site visitor to your FAQ page if they have a common question about your products or services.</p>\n<p>On that same form, you might also want to redirect site visitors to your developer documentation if their question is more technical in nature.</p>\n<p>For help with this, be sure to check out our easy to follow tutorial on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-multiple-form-confirmations-in-wpforms/\">creating multiple form confirmations</a> in WPForms.</p>\n<p>And be sure to check out how to use <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/inspiring-uses-of-conditional-logic-to-boost-form-conversions/\">WPFormsâ smart conditional logic</a> to make this happen.</p>\n<h3>How to Publish a WordPress Form that Redirects Users</h3>\n<p>Once youâve configured your formâs redirects, and <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/setup-form-notification-wpforms/\">set up form notifications</a> to make sure everyone that needs to know a form has been submitted will be notified, it&#8217;s time to publish your form.</p>\n<p>WPForms allows you to add your forms to many locations on your website, including your blog posts, pages, and even <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-add-a-contact-form-in-wordpress-sidebar-widget/\">sidebar widgets</a>.</p>\n<p>Letâs take a look at the most common post/page embed option.</p>\n<p>To start, create a new post or page in WordPress and then click on the <strong>Add Form</strong> button.</p>\n<p>Next, select your order form in the modal popup and click <strong>Add Form</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-206108\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/Add-Form-Dropdown-Menu.png\" alt=\"Add Form Dropdown Menu\" width=\"606\" height=\"363\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/Add-Form-Dropdown-Menu.png 606w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/Add-Form-Dropdown-Menu-300x180.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 606px) 100vw, 606px\" /></p>\n<p>After that simply publish your page and view it.</p>\n<p>Below is an example of our form:</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-298456\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/published-contact-form.png\" alt=\"published contact form\" width=\"562\" height=\"371\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/published-contact-form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/published-contact-form-300x198.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>You can combine your forms with our email marketing addons like <a title=\"How to Install and Use MailChimp Addon with WPForms\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/install-use-mailchimp-addon-wpforms/\">MailChimp</a>, <a title=\"How to Install and Use AWeber Addon with WPForms\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/install-use-aweber-addon-wpforms/\">AWeber</a>, <a title=\"How to Install and Use GetResponse Addon with WPForms\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-install-and-use-getresponse-addon-with-wpforms/\">GetResponse</a>, <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-install-and-use-the-drip-addon-in-wpforms/\">Drip</a>, <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-connect-constant-contact-with-wpforms/\">Constant Contact</a>, and <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-install-and-use-campaign-monitor-addon-with-wpforms/\">Campaign Monitor</a>.</p>\n<p>This allows you to automatically add all potential customers to your <a title=\"Beginner\'s Guide to Email Marketing\" href=\"http://optinmonster.com/beginners-guide-to-email-marketing/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">email marketing list</a>. You can even add them into various marketing automation sequences from there to improve your conversions.</p>\n<p>And there you have it! You now know how to redirect users after a WordPress form submission.</p>\n<p>In addition, you might want to check out our guide on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-file-upload-form-in-wordpress/\">how to create a file upload form in WordPress</a> soÂ you can collect all the information you need from site visitors at once, minimizing the back and forth conversations and providing a better experience.</p>\n<p>So, what are you waiting for? Get started with the most powerful <a href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WordPress forms plugin</a> today.</p>\n<p>And donât forget, if you like this article, then please follow us on <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/wpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> and <a href=\"http://twitter.com/easywpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-redirect-users-after-a-wordpress-form-submit/\">How to Redirect Users after a WordPress Form Submission</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:77:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-redirect-users-after-a-wordpress-form-submit/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:2:\"30\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:3;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:54:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:49:\"How to Limit the Number of WordPress Form Entries\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:70:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-limit-the-number-of-wordpress-form-entries/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:78:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-limit-the-number-of-wordpress-form-entries/#respond\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Mon, 22 Oct 2018 12:00:10 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:5:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:19:\"WordPress Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:12:\"form entries\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"subscribe\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:17:\"form locker addon\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"limit entries\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:29:\"https://wpforms.com/?p=297730\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:584:\"<p>Do you want to learn how to limit the number of WordPress form entries submitted on your website? Sometimes capping the number of form entries submitted is easier than manually monitoring how many people have clicked submit. In this article, weâll show you how to limit the number of WordPress form entries on your website [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-limit-the-number-of-wordpress-form-entries/\">How to Limit the Number of WordPress Form Entries</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"Lindsay Liedke\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:11136:\"<p>Do you want to learn how to limit the number of WordPress form entries submitted on your website? Sometimes capping the number of form entries submitted is easier than manually monitoring how many people have clicked submit.</p>\n<p>In this article, weâll show you how to limit the number of WordPress form entries on your website using WPFormsâ Form Locker addon.</p>\n<h3>Why Limit Form Submissions?</h3>\n<p>As weâve mentioned before, in out post about <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-enable-wordpress-form-scheduling-step-by-step/\">enabling the WordPress form scheduling</a>, your websiteâs forms are usually available all the time so site visitors can get in touch with you whenever they need.</p>\n<p>That said, sometimes you might feel the need to limit the number of forms that people submit on your website.</p>\n<p>For instance, maybe youâre hosting an event that has a maximum number of people that can attend, so you want to limit the number of <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-make-an-event-registration-form-in-wordpress/\">event registration forms</a> that people can submit on your site.</p>\n<p>Or, perhaps you have an opening at your place of employment and you want to limit the number of <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-job-application-form-in-wordpress/\">job application forms</a> so you donât have to review too many.</p>\n<p>Better yet, maybe youâre using WPFormsâ <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/features/form-templates/\">Form Templates Pack addon</a> to create a contest or sweepstakes on your website and you only want a certain number of people participating.</p>\n<p>No matter the reason for wanting to stop form submissions after a certain number of them have been processed, read on to find out how WPForms makes doing this a cinch.</p>\n<h3>Step 1: Create a New WordPress Form</h3>\n<p>The first thing youâll need to do is install and activate the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/pricing/\">WPForms plugin</a>. For more details, see this step by step guide on <a title=\"Step by step guide on How to Install a WordPress Plugin\" href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/step-by-step-guide-to-install-a-wordpress-plugin-for-beginners/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">how to install a plugin in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>Next, youâll need to install and activate the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/form-locker-addon/\">Form Locker addon</a>.</p>\n<p>To do this, go to <strong>WPForms</strong> Â» <strong>Addon</strong> and find the one labeled <strong>Form Locker addon</strong>.</p>\n<p>Click <strong>Install Addon</strong> and then <strong>Activate</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-290577\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-addon.png\" alt=\"form locker addon\" width=\"562\" height=\"200\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-addon.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-addon-300x107.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Now youâll need to create a new form.</p>\n<p>You can enable the entry limit feature on any WordPress form you create using WPForms. Thatâs because we strive to make form creation as easy as possible, while still offering our customer a ton of cool features for creating one-of-a-kind forms.</p>\n<p>For our example, weâll create a simple contest entry form using the Form Templates pack addon mentioned above. For help with this addon, that has over 100 different templates for you to choose from, check out this documentation on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-install-and-use-the-form-templates-pack-addon/\">installing and using this flexible addon</a>.</p>\n<p>Once the Form Templates Pack addon is installed and activated, choose the <strong>Contest Entry Form</strong> template and let WPForms create a form for you.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-297733\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/contest-entry-form.png\" alt=\"contest entry form\" width=\"562\" height=\"613\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/contest-entry-form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/contest-entry-form-275x300.png 275w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>You can add additional fields to your form by dragging them from the left hand panel to the right hand panel.</p>\n<p>Then, click on the field to make any changes. You can also click on a form field and drag it to rearrange the order on your WordPress form.</p>\n<p>When your form looks the way you want it to, click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Step 2: Enable Entry Limits</h3>\n<p>Once your form is customized and saved, go to <strong>Settings</strong> Â» <strong>Form Locker</strong> in the Form Editor. This will bring up the different settings you can configure for the Form Locker addon.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-293951\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-settings-1.png\" alt=\"form locker settings\" width=\"562\" height=\"334\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-settings-1.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-settings-1-300x178.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Click on the <strong>Entry Limit</strong> checkbox to enable form submission limits.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-297734\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-entry-limit-checkbox.png\" alt=\"form locker entry limit checkbox\" width=\"562\" height=\"354\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-entry-limit-checkbox.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-entry-limit-checkbox-300x189.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>When you click on <strong>Entry Limit</strong> selection, youâll see a few settings to configure:</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-297736\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-entry-limit-settings.png\" alt=\"form locker entry limit settings\" width=\"562\" height=\"530\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-entry-limit-settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-entry-limit-settings-300x283.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Limit:</strong> the maximum number of form entries youâll allow for your form.</li>\n<li><strong>Closed Message:</strong> the message that will display to site visitors trying to submit your form after the entry limit has been reached.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Hereâs an example of what our contest entry form looks like when weâve limited the number of form entries to 100:</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-297743\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-entry-limit-example.png\" alt=\"form entry limit example\" width=\"562\" height=\"515\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-entry-limit-example.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-entry-limit-example-300x275.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Cick <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<p>WPForms integrates with the following <a href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/showcase/best-email-marketing-services/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">email services providers</a>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/aweber-addon/\">AWeber</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/mailchimp-addon/\">MailChimp</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/drip-addon/\">Drip</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/features/constant-contact/\">Constant Contact</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/campaign-monitor-addon/\">Campaign Monitor</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/getresponse-addon/\">GetResponse</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>For help with adding a newsletter checkbox to your contest entry form, or any other form for that matter, check out this tutorial on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-add-a-mailchimp-signup-checkbox-to-your-contact-form/\">how to add a MailChimp subscribe checkbox to your WordPress forms</a>.</p>\n<h3>Step 3: Prevent Multiple Form Entries</h3>\n<p>If you want to prevent the same user from submitting more than one form entry, you can require unique values for certain form fields.</p>\n<p>For instance, you can require unique answers for the following field types:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Single Line Text</li>\n<li>Name</li>\n<li>Email</li>\n<li>Website / URL</li>\n<li>Password</li>\n<li>Phone</li>\n</ul>\n<p>To enable this feature, go to your contest entry form and click on the field you want to require unique answers on. Then, scroll down to <strong>Advanced Options</strong> and click the checkbox labeled <strong>Require unique answer</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-297738\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/require-unique-answer.png\" alt=\"require unique answer\" width=\"562\" height=\"550\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/require-unique-answer.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/require-unique-answer-300x294.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Now, any time someone tries to submit a form on your site that has already been submitted, theyâll see the message âThe value must be unique.â</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-297739\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/unique-value-example.png\" alt=\"unique value example\" width=\"562\" height=\"113\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/unique-value-example.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/unique-value-example-300x60.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>And there you have it! You now know how to limit the number of WordPress form entries on your website so you donât get too many form submissions.</p>\n<p>If you want to collect statistics and generate reports on the data collected in your WordPress forms, check out how to use the WPForms <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-install-and-use-the-surveys-and-polls-addon/\">Surveys and Polls addon</a> to take your formâs functionality to the next level.</p>\n<p>And if youâre still not sure WPForms is the right solution for you, <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/user-reviews/\">see what others have to say about WPForms</a> and find out why over 1 million websites choose WPForms to build their WordPress forms.</p>\n<p>So, what are you waiting for? Get started with the most powerful <a href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WordPress forms plugin</a> today.</p>\n<p>And donât forget, if you like this article, then please follow us on <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/wpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> and <a href=\"http://twitter.com/easywpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-limit-the-number-of-wordpress-form-entries/\">How to Limit the Number of WordPress Form Entries</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:75:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-limit-the-number-of-wordpress-form-entries/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:4;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:57:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:39:\"How to Create an RSVP Form in WordPress\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:60:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-an-rsvp-form-in-wordpress/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:69:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-an-rsvp-form-in-wordpress/#comments\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Thu, 18 Oct 2018 12:00:32 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:6:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:19:\"WordPress Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:7:\"contact\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:4:\"rsvp\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"ticket\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:19:\"form templates pack\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:5;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"rsvp form\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:27:\"https://wpforms.com/?p=1214\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:555:\"<p>Do you need a way to handle event registrations? Are you looking to collect information without using snail mail? Using an RSVP form can simplify your event management needs. In this article, weâll show you how to create an RSVP form in WordPress. Why Use an RSVP Form? Your time is limited. Spending time opening [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-an-rsvp-form-in-wordpress/\">How to Create an RSVP Form in WordPress</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"Lindsay Liedke\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:16192:\"<p>Do you need a way to handle event registrations? Are you looking to collect information without using snail mail? Using an RSVP form can simplify your event management needs.</p>\n<p>In this article, weâll show you how to create an RSVP form in WordPress.</p>\n<h3>Why Use an RSVP Form?</h3>\n<p>Your time is limited. Spending time opening letters in the mail, jotting down the details, and then compiling all the data together isn&#8217;t efficient.</p>\n<p>Not to mention, making the RSVP process easier for your guests should be your top priority. Youâll get a higher response rate by sharing a link to confirm rather than tasking them to send their replies via snail mail.</p>\n<p>If you have a <a title=\"How to Install WordPress\" href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/how-to-install-wordpress/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">WordPress site</a>, you can quickly get all the information you need in an organized format with an online RSVP form.</p>\n<p>Some events you might want to use an RSVP form for include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Birthday party</strong> &#8211; Get a quick headcount of attendees.</li>\n<li><strong>Wedding</strong> &#8211; Ask for additional details like meal preferences.</li>\n<li><strong>Business event</strong> &#8211; Accept registrations and even sell tickets on your RSVP form.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>So, letâs see how to create an RSVP form in WordPress.</p>\n<h3>Step 1: Create an RSVP Form in WordPress</h3>\n<p>Using WPForms is the easiest way to create an online RSVP form in WordPress. WPForms comes with the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/form-templates-pack-addon/\">Form Templates Pack addon</a> that allows you to choose from a huge variety of pre-built templates for every niche and industry, including tons of different online RSVP form templates.</p>\n<p>The first thing youâll need to do is install and activate the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/pricing/\">WPForms plugin</a>. For more details, see this step by step guide on <a title=\"Step by step guide on How to Install a WordPress Plugin\" href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/step-by-step-guide-to-install-a-wordpress-plugin-for-beginners/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">how to install a plugin in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>Next, youâll need to install and activate the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-install-and-use-the-form-templates-pack-addon/\">Form Templates Pack addon</a>.</p>\n<p>To do this, go to <strong>WPForms</strong> Â» <strong>Addon</strong> and find the one labeled <strong>Form Templates Pack addon</strong>.</p>\n<p>Click <strong>Install Addon</strong> and then <strong>Activate</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-291194\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-templates-pack-addon.png\" alt=\"form templates pack addon\" width=\"562\" height=\"193\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-templates-pack-addon.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-templates-pack-addon-300x103.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Now youâll need to create a new form.</p>\n<p>To do this, go to <strong>WPForms</strong> Â» <strong>Add New </strong>and name your form. Then, scroll down to the section labeled <strong>Additional Templates</strong> and type âRSVPâ into the search bar.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-295707\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/rsvp-form-templates.png\" alt=\"rsvp form templates\" width=\"562\" height=\"456\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/rsvp-form-templates.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/rsvp-form-templates-300x243.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Youâll find the following RSVP form templates in our Form Templates Pack addon:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Birthday Party Invitation RSVP Form</li>\n<li>New Years Party RSVP Form</li>\n<li>Party Invitation RSVP Form</li>\n<li>Potluck Invitation RSVP Form</li>\n<li>Simple RSVP Form</li>\n<li>Super Bowl Party RSVP Form</li>\n<li>Wedding Party RSVP Form</li>\n</ul>\n<p>In our example, weâll choose the <strong>Birthday Party Invitation RSVP Form</strong>.</p>\n<p>When the pre-built form template loads, most of the work is already done. In fact, youâll find the following fields in the form:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Will you be able to make it? (Yeah, Maybe, I canât)</li>\n<li>How many people are you going to bring?</li>\n<li>Comments or Questions</li>\n</ul>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-295708\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/rsvp-form.png\" alt=\"rsvp form\" width=\"562\" height=\"321\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/rsvp-form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/rsvp-form-300x171.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>You can add additional fields to your form by dragging them from the left hand panel to the right hand panel.</p>\n<p>Then, click on the field to make any changes. You can also click on a form field and drag it to rearrange the order on your RSVP form.</p>\n<p>If your RSVP form is for a business event, you can request attendees to pay for their tickets when they RSVP.</p>\n<p>WPForms allows you to accept payments on your forms using either <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/stripe-addon/\">Stripe</a> or <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/paypal-standard-addon/\">PayPal</a>. You can read our documentation on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-allow-users-to-choose-a-payment-method-on-your-form/\">how to allow users to choose a payment method</a> if you want to use both integrations on your form.</p>\n<p>When your RSVP form looks the way you want it to, click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Step 2: Configure Your RSVP Form Settings</h3>\n<p>To start, go to <strong>Settings</strong> Â» <strong>General</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-246850\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-General-Settings.png\" alt=\"WPForms General Settings\" width=\"562\" height=\"443\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-General-Settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-General-Settings-300x236.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Here you can configure the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Form Name.</strong> Rename your form here.</li>\n<li><strong>Form Description.</strong> Give your form a description.</li>\n<li><strong>Submit Button Text.</strong> Customize the copy on the submit button.</li>\n<li><strong>Spam Prevention.</strong> <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-build-a-spam-free-contact-form-without-captcha/\">Enable the anti-spam honeypot feature</a> to prevent spam form submissions and <a href=\"https://www.wpbeginner.com/wordpress-security/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">keep your website secure</a>. This feature is automatically enabled on all WordPress forms. If you decide to use another form of spam prevention, you can either unclick this option or continue using this feature with other spam prevention features such as recaptcha.</li>\n<li><strong>GDPR Enhancements.</strong> You can disable the storing of entry information and user details, such as IP addresses and user agents, in an effort to <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-create-gdpr-compliant-forms/\">comply with GDPR requirements</a>. In addition, check out our step by step instructions on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-add-a-gdpr-agreement-field-to-your-sites-forms/\">how to add a GDPR agreement field to your simple contact form</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Step 3: Configure Your RSVP Formâs Notifications</h3>\n<p>Notifications are a great way to send an email whenever an order is submitted on your website.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-246852\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-Notifications-Settings.png\" alt=\"WPForms Notifications Settings\" width=\"562\" height=\"228\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-Notifications-Settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-Notifications-Settings-300x122.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>In fact, unless you disable this feature, whenever someone submits an RSVP form on your site, youâll get a notification about it.</p>\n<p>If you <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-use-smart-tags-in-wpforms/\">use smart tags</a>, you can also send a notification to the site visitor when they RSVP to your event, letting them know you received their RSVP and will be in contact shortly. This assures people their form has gone through properly.</p>\n<p>For help with this step, check out our documentation on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/setup-form-notification-wpforms/\">how to set up form notifications in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>WPForms lets you notify the right person in your organization when an RSVP form is submitted. For instance, you can send a notification to yourself, your attendee, and the event coordinator in charge of meals.</p>\n<p>For help doing this, check out our step by step tutorial on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-multiple-form-notifications-in-wordpress-forms/\">how to send multiple form notifications in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>Lastly, if you want to keep branding across your emails consistent, you can check out this guide on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-add-custom-header-image-in-your-wpforms-email-template/\">adding a custom header to your email template</a>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-211599\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Custom-Email-Header.jpg\" alt=\"Custom Email Header\" width=\"562\" height=\"314\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Custom-Email-Header.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Custom-Email-Header-300x168.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<h3>Step 4: Configure Your RSVP Formâs Confirmations</h3>\n<p>Form confirmations are messages that display to site visitors once they submit an RSVP form on your website. They let people know that their form has been processed and offer you the chance to let them know what the next steps are.</p>\n<p>WPForms has three confirmation types:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Message.</strong> This is the default confirmation type in WPForms. When someone submits an RSVP form, a simple message confirmation will appear letting them know their form was processed. Look here for some <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/form-success-message-ideas-to-boost-customer-happiness/\">great success messages</a> to help boost customer happiness.</li>\n<li><strong>Show Page.</strong> This confirmation type will take site visitors to a specific web page on your site thanking them for their RSVP answer and telling them when youâll be in touch with help. For help doing this, check out our tutorial on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-redirect-users-after-wordpress-form-submit/\">redirecting customers to a thank you page</a>. In addition, be sure to check out our article on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/4-thank-you-page-examples-to-boost-customer-loyalty/\">creating effective Thank You pages</a> for boosting customer loyalty.</li>\n<li><strong>Go to URL (Redirect).</strong> This option is used when you want to send site visitors to a different website.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Letâs see <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/setup-form-confirmation-wpforms/\">how to set up a simple form confirmation in WPForms</a> so you can customize the message site visitors will see when they RSVP to your event.</p>\n<p>To start, click on the <strong>Confirmation</strong> tab in the Form Editor under <strong>Settings</strong>.</p>\n<p>Next, select the type of confirmation type youâd like to create. For this example, weâll select <strong>Message</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-238574\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/WPForms-Confirmation-Settings.png\" alt=\"WPForms Confirmation Settings\" width=\"562\" height=\"260\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/WPForms-Confirmation-Settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/WPForms-Confirmation-Settings-300x139.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Then, customize the confirmation message to your liking and click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<p>If you want to display different confirmations to site visitors based on their behavior, be sure to read up on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-create-conditional-form-confirmations/\">how to create conditional form confirmations</a>.</p>\n<h3>Step 5: Connect Your Form With a Third-Party App</h3>\n<p>WPForms allows you to easily connect your WordPress form with your favorite third-party app using our <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/zapier-addon/\">Zapier addon</a>. In fact, the Zapier addon lets you connect your WordPress forms to over 500+ web apps.</p>\n<p>For example, you can connect your form with your Google Calendar with ease. That way, any time someone RSVPâs to your event, the information on the form will automatically add to your calendar.</p>\n<p>To see how to do this, check out this article on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-client-booking-form-in-wordpress/\">how to connect your form with Google Calendar</a>.</p>\n<h3>Step 6: Add Your RSVP Form to Your Website</h3>\n<p>After youâve created an RSVP form, you need to add it to your WordPress website.</p>\n<p>WPForms allows you to add your forms to many locations on your website, including your blog posts, pages, and even <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-add-a-contact-form-in-wordpress-sidebar-widget/\">sidebar widgets</a>.</p>\n<p>Letâs take a look at the most common post/page embed option.</p>\n<p>To start, create a new post or page in WordPress and then click on the <strong>Add Form</strong> button.</p>\n<p>Next, select your order form in the modal popup and click <strong>Add Form</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-295705\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/add-rsvp-form.png\" alt=\"add rsvp form\" width=\"562\" height=\"328\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/add-rsvp-form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/add-rsvp-form-300x175.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Then, publish your post or page so your RSVP form will appear on your website.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-295706\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/final-RSVP-form.png\" alt=\"final RSVP form\" width=\"562\" height=\"488\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/final-RSVP-form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/final-RSVP-form-300x260.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>And there you have it! You now know how to create an RSVP form in WordPress.</p>\n<p>You can connect your RSVP forms with your email newsletter services such as <a title=\"AWeber Addon\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/aweber-addon/\">AWeber</a>, <a title=\"MailChimp Addon\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/mailchimp-addon/\">MailChimp</a>, <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/features/constant-contact/\">Constant Contact</a>, <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/getresponse-addon/\">GetResponse</a>, <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/campaign-monitor-addon/\">Campaign Monitor</a>, or <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/drip-addon/\">Drip</a> to automatically add new users to your email list and send out updates about your upcoming event.</p>\n<p>So, what are you waiting for? Get started with the most powerful <a href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WordPress forms plugin</a> today.</p>\n<p>And donât forget, if you like this article, then please follow us on <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/wpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> and <a href=\"http://twitter.com/easywpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-an-rsvp-form-in-wordpress/\">How to Create an RSVP Form in WordPress</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:65:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-an-rsvp-form-in-wordpress/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"2\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:5;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:54:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:88:\"6 Email Branding Tips for Small Businesses: How to Stand Out And Conquer the Competition\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:61:\"https://wpforms.com/email-branding-tips-for-small-businesses/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:69:\"https://wpforms.com/email-branding-tips-for-small-businesses/#respond\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Wed, 17 Oct 2018 12:00:25 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:5:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Marketing\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:20:\"html email templates\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"notifications\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:18:\"email notification\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"branding tips\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:29:\"https://wpforms.com/?p=126054\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:613:\"<p>Are you wondering how to brand your emails and make them look professional? Emails you send users after they submit a form and future email campaigns help you encourage people to come back to your website and keep them engaged with your brand. With the right email branding techniques, you can strengthen brand recall among [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/email-branding-tips-for-small-businesses/\">6 Email Branding Tips for Small Businesses: How to Stand Out And Conquer the Competition</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"Lindsay Liedke\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:15816:\"<p>Are you wondering how to brand your emails and make them look professional? Emails you send users after they submit a form and future email campaigns help you encourage people to come back to your website and keep them engaged with your brand. With the right email branding techniques, you can strengthen brand recall among your users.</p>\n<p>In this article, weâll take a look at a few email branding tips for small businesses.</p>\n<h3>1. Choose a Header Image</h3>\n<p>Did you know you can customize the email notification templates of WPForms? WPForms allows you to choose a pretty HTML template or basic template for your notifications.</p>\n<p>By default, a professional HTML template is chosen that enables you to add a custom header image to brand your emails.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-113650\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/email-template.jpg\" alt=\"email template\" width=\"562\" height=\"314\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/email-template.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/email-template-300x168.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>With custom email templates, you can personalize the thank you emails you send out to your leads or people who <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-non-profit-donation-form/\">donate to your nonprofit organization</a>.</p>\n<p>If youâre selling a product on your site, you can use this feature to brand the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/create-invoice-wpforms/\">invoice you send to your customers</a> after every sale. For help deciding how to invoice your customers, check out our roundup of the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/the-best-invoicing-software-for-your-wordpress-order-forms/\">best invoicing software for your WordPress forms</a>.</p>\n<p>Lastly, if youâre an agency, you can use it as a nice perk you offer to your clients to make your services stand out. After all, helping your clients to better brand their business goes beyond what many agencies do for their customers.</p>\n<p>Hereâs how to choose a header image in your email notification template.</p>\n<p>Of course, you&#8217;ll have to install <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/pricing/\">WPForms</a> on your site as the first step. Learn <a href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/step-by-step-guide-to-install-a-wordpress-plugin-for-beginners/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">how to install a WordPress plugin</a> if you need help.</p>\n<p>Next, click on <strong>WPForms Â» Settings</strong> and select the <strong>Email</strong> tab at the top.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-294672\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/email-template-settings.png\" alt=\"email template settings\" width=\"562\" height=\"323\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/email-template-settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/email-template-settings-300x172.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Then, scroll down to the Header Image section and click on the <strong>Upload Image</strong> button.</p>\n<p><img class=\"size-full wp-image-112689 alignleft\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/upload-image.jpg\" alt=\"Upload image button\" width=\"562\" height=\"98\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/upload-image.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/upload-image-300x52.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>An overlay will appear where you can upload a new file or select an existing file from the WordPress Media Library.</p>\n<div class=\"alert alert-info\">Note: For the best support on all devices, the recommended image size is 300&#215;100 pixels.</div>\n<p>After selecting your image, click on <strong>Use Image</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-294677\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/use-image-in-email-header.png\" alt=\"use image in email header\" width=\"562\" height=\"304\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/use-image-in-email-header.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/use-image-in-email-header-300x162.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Finally, click on <strong>Save Settings</strong> to keep the changes.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-294671\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/email-header-image-save.png\" alt=\"email header image save\" width=\"562\" height=\"267\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/email-header-image-save.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/email-header-image-save-300x143.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>To test this template, send a notification email to yourself by submitting a form entry. For help with this step, check out our documentation on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-properly-test-your-wordpress-forms-before-launching-checklist/#email-delivery\">how to test forms before they go live</a>.</p>\n<p>And if you notice you&#8217;re having problems receiving from form notifications, don&#8217;t worry, we have a solution for that too. Check out this information on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-fix-wordpress-contact-form-not-sending-email-with-smtp/\">how to use our sister plugin, WP SMTP</a>, to help.</p>\n<h3>2. Customize the Email Background Color</h3>\n<p>WPForms also allows you to choose a background color for your emails. To give your brand a consistent look, use the same background color in your emails that you use on your website.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-294670\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/email-background-color.png\" alt=\"email background color\" width=\"562\" height=\"362\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/email-background-color.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/email-background-color-300x193.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>WPForms comes with a color picker that allows you to choose the exact color you want to use in your emails. If you prefer, you can specify the hex code in the background color field.</p>\n<h3>3. Personalize Your Emails</h3>\n<p>Email personalization can mean the difference between emails your recipients&#8217; notice and click, and emails they skip right over. No matter how well you brand your notification templates, theyâre useless unless your recipients click on your emails.</p>\n<p>WPForms allows you to send a personalized notification email to those who submit your form without any expensive email marketing tool.</p>\n<p>By default, any time someone submits a form on your website, youâll be sent an email notification about the form submission. But WPForms takes it one step further and lets you <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-multiple-form-notifications-in-wordpress-forms/\">create multiple form notifications</a> when you want to send personalized emails to others such as a team member or the user who submitted the form.</p>\n<p>To do this, go to <strong>Settings Â» Notification</strong> and select <strong>Add New Notification.</strong></p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-294668\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/add-new-notification.png\" alt=\"add new notification\" width=\"562\" height=\"243\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/add-new-notification.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/add-new-notification-300x130.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>A popup modal will appear. Enter a name for your new notification. This name is for your internal reference only, so name it whatever you want.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-294685\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/new-notification-name.png\" alt=\"new notification name\" width=\"562\" height=\"331\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/new-notification-name.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/new-notification-name-300x177.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Click <strong>OK</strong>.</p>\n<p>Under the section labeled <strong>Send To Email Address</strong>, erase the text {admin_email}. Then, click on <strong>Show Smart Tags</strong> and then <strong>Email</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-294676\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/smart-tags.png\" alt=\"smart tags\" width=\"562\" height=\"96\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/smart-tags.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/smart-tags-300x51.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Youâll notice a short bit of code, which is the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-use-smart-tags-in-wpforms/\">smart tag</a>, appear. It will look like {field_id=&#8221;#&#8221;}, where # is replaced with the specific field number on your form. This smart tag will automatically fill in the email address that the user inputs when filling out the form.</p>\n<p>Next, you can customize the message that users will receive.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-294675\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/notification-message.png\" alt=\"notification message\" width=\"562\" height=\"212\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/notification-message.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/notification-message-300x113.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Here you can add the information that the user filled out on your form, as well as a personalized message thanking them or letting them know what the next steps are.</p>\n<p>If part of your email notification includes a lead magnet, check out this tutorial on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-send-a-pdf-attachment-in-a-form-notification-email/\">how to send a PDF attachment in a form notification email</a>.</p>\n<p>This added personal touch will show your customers that you care enough to take the time to write a special message to them, rather than just send out generic bulk messages to everyone.</p>\n<h3>4. Add Visuals</h3>\n<p>Sometimes adding an eye-catching image to your emails is the best way to brand yourself and set your business apart from the competition. In fact, a visually appealing image in your email may be just what you need to encourage people to click on your CTA button and return to your website.</p>\n<p>Here are some ideas of images you can include in your emails to site visitors, depending on what the email campaign is all about:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Blog post image to promote new content</li>\n<li>Product image to promote a new release or an upcoming sale</li>\n<li>Video content to entice people to want to learn more and click through</li>\n<li>Images of you, your team, and happy customers to build trust</li>\n<li>Social media images to promote your social profiles and get people to like or follow you</li>\n</ul>\n<p>People process images <a href=\"https://www.liveplan.com/blog/scientific-reasons-why-you-should-present-your-data-visually/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">60,000 time faster</a> than text. Thatâs why grabbing their attention right away, especially if theyâre planning to skim your email, is a great strategy for getting people to take action.</p>\n<p>For example, in one of our feature release emails, we added an image to the email thatâs clickable:</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-294673\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/image-in-email-campaign.png\" alt=\"image in email campaign\" width=\"562\" height=\"603\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/image-in-email-campaign.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/image-in-email-campaign-280x300.png 280w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>This not only breaks up the text a bit, itâs perfect for those that want to get right to the blog post and start reading about our newest feature.</p>\n<p>The great thing about <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/features/constant-contact/\">Constant Contact</a>, which integrates seamlessly with WPForms, is that they let you add images to your email campaigns in the following ways:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Choose from millions of stock images that are both free and premium</li>\n<li>Store your own images and documents in your account so you can upload and use your own images</li>\n<li>Upload photos from Facebook or Instagram and easily add them to your emails</li>\n</ul>\n<p>You donât always have to add images to your emails as a way to brand them and stand out from the crowd. But, if you have something important coming up, and really want to get people back to your site to check it out, adding an image might be the way to get more clicks.</p>\n<h3>5. Include Relevant Links</h3>\n<p>Another great way to brand your emails, is to add relevant links where appropriate. This can be in addition to CTA buttons that encourage people to buy, donate, register, etc., or instead of them. The point is to get people to move past your email and somewhere else your business thrives.</p>\n<p>For example, add a link back to your newest blog post that highlights a new feature release, like we do here at WPForms:</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-294674\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/link-to-new-content.png\" alt=\"link to new content\" width=\"562\" height=\"432\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/link-to-new-content.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/link-to-new-content-300x231.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Or, add social media links to encourage people to like or follow you on popular social media networks like Facebook, Instagram, Pinterest, LinkedIn, and Twitter.</p>\n<p>Adding links to your emails not only serve to strengthen the relationships you have with subscribers, both old and new, they help you expose your brand further than you could even imagine.</p>\n<h3>6. Keep Consistent Branding</h3>\n<p>Customers want to do business with the brands they know. Brand consistency is part of building that trust and recognition.</p>\n<p>Whenever you design your marketing materials, including your email notifications and future email campaigns, make them consistent with your brand. By using a consistent brand appearance for all your marketing materials, you can set yourself apart from the competition while strengthening brand recall among your leads and customers. This way you can ensure that your users will never have a second thought as to where the email they are reading came from.</p>\n<p>And here you have it! You now know some cool email branding tips for small businesses.</p>\n<p>If youâre looking to <a href=\"http://optinmonster.com/beginners-guide-to-email-marketing/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">grow your email list</a>, using the right tools is essential. Read about the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/best-wordpress-lead-generation-plugins-to-grow-your-email-list/\">4 best lead generation plugins to grow your list here</a>.</p>\n<p>So, what are you waiting for? Get started with the most powerful <a href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WordPress forms plugin</a> today.</p>\n<p>And donât forget, if you like this article, then please follow us on <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/wpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> and <a href=\"http://twitter.com/easywpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/email-branding-tips-for-small-businesses/\">6 Email Branding Tips for Small Businesses: How to Stand Out And Conquer the Competition</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:66:\"https://wpforms.com/email-branding-tips-for-small-businesses/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:6;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:57:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:54:\"How to Enable WordPress Form Scheduling (Step by Step)\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:73:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-enable-wordpress-form-scheduling-step-by-step/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:81:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-enable-wordpress-form-scheduling-step-by-step/#respond\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Tue, 16 Oct 2018 12:00:33 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:6:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:19:\"WordPress Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:11:\"application\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"rsvp form\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:11:\"survey form\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:17:\"form locker addon\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:5;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:15:\"form scheduling\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:29:\"https://wpforms.com/?p=293945\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:586:\"<p>Do you want to schedule a start and stop date that your WordPress forms will be accessible to site visitors? Learning how to enable WordPress form scheduling ensures that your forms only remain available for submission for a set amount of time. In this article, weâll show you how to use the scheduling feature found [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-enable-wordpress-form-scheduling-step-by-step/\">How to Enable WordPress Form Scheduling (Step by Step)</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"Lindsay Liedke\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9505:\"<p>Do you want to schedule a start and stop date that your WordPress forms will be accessible to site visitors? Learning how to enable WordPress form scheduling ensures that your forms only remain available for submission for a set amount of time.</p>\n<p>In this article, weâll show you how to use the scheduling feature found in WPFormsâ Form Locker addon so people can only submit forms on your WordPress website when you want them to.</p>\n<h3>Why Enable Form Scheduling?</h3>\n<p>Your WordPress forms are generally available to site visitors day and night so they can get in contact with you whenever they need to.</p>\n<p>For instance, you might have a <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-simple-contact-form-in-wordpress/\">simple contact form</a> on your siteâs Contact page, an <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-simple-order-form-in-wordpress/\">order form that collects payments</a> using Stripe or PayPal, or a <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-user-registration-form-in-wordpress/\">user registration form</a> so loyal followers can access locked content after paying their dues.</p>\n<p>However, there may be times when you want to limit the time your WordPress forms are available to site visitors.</p>\n<p>For example, you might enable WordPress form scheduling to limit the time the following types of forms can be submitted:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/surveys-and-polls-addon/\">Online surveys or polls</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-job-application-form-in-wordpress/\">Job applications</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-make-an-event-registration-form-in-wordpress/\">Event registrations</a></li>\n<li>Sweepstakes or contest forms</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-set-up-a-volunteer-application-form-in-wordpress/\">Volunteer applications</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-an-rsvp-form-in-wordpress/\">RSVPs to a party</a></li>\n<li>Or any other type of WordPress form that may have a time limit</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If youâve decided that you need to limit the time your WordPress form is open for submission, keep reading to find out how to enable WordPress form scheduling on your siteâs forms using WPForms.</p>\n<h3>Step 1: Create a New WordPress Form</h3>\n<p>The first thing youâll need to do is install and activate the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/pricing/\">WPForms plugin</a>. For more details, see this step by step guide on <a title=\"Step by step guide on How to Install a WordPress Plugin\" href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/step-by-step-guide-to-install-a-wordpress-plugin-for-beginners/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">how to install a plugin in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>Next, youâll need to install and activate the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/form-locker-addon/\">Form Locker addon</a>.</p>\n<p>To do this, go to <strong>WPForms</strong> Â» <strong>Addon</strong> and find the one labeled <strong>Form Locker addon</strong>.</p>\n<p>Click <strong>Install Addon</strong> and then <strong>Activate</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-290577\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-addon.png\" alt=\"form locker addon\" width=\"562\" height=\"200\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-addon.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-addon-300x107.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Now youâll need to create a new form.</p>\n<p>You can enable the form scheduling feature on any WordPress form you create using WPForms. Thatâs because we strive to make form creation as easy as possible, while still offering our customers a slew of neat features to take advantage of.</p>\n<p>For our example, weâll create a party invitation RSVP form using the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/features/form-templates/\">Form Templates Pack addon</a>.</p>\n<p>For help using the Form Templates Pack addon, check out our helpful documentation on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-install-and-use-the-form-templates-pack-addon/\">installing and using this flexible addon</a> that has over 100 different form templates to choose from.</p>\n<p>Once the Form Templates Pack addon is installed and activated, simply choose the <strong>Party Invitation RSVP Form</strong> template and let WPForms create a form for you.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-293952\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/party-invitation-rsvp-form.png\" alt=\"party invitation rsvp form\" width=\"562\" height=\"443\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/party-invitation-rsvp-form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/party-invitation-rsvp-form-300x236.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>You can add additional fields to your form by dragging them from the left hand panel to the right hand panel.</p>\n<p>Then, click on the field to make any changes. You can also click on a form field and drag it to rearrange the order on your WordPress form.</p>\n<p>When your form looks the way you want it to, click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Step 2: Enable WordPress Form Scheduling</h3>\n<p>Once your form is customized and saved, go to <strong>Settings</strong> Â» <strong>Form Locker</strong> in the Form Editor. This will bring up the different settings you can configure for the Form Locker addon.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-293951\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-settings-1.png\" alt=\"form locker settings\" width=\"562\" height=\"334\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-settings-1.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-settings-1-300x178.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Click on the <strong>Scheduling</strong> checkbox to enable form scheduling.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-293950\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-settings-with-four-options.png\" alt=\"form locker settings with four options\" width=\"562\" height=\"368\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-settings-with-four-options.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-settings-with-four-options-300x196.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>When you click on the <strong>Scheduling</strong> selection, youâll see a few settings to configure:</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-293949\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-scheduling-settings.png\" alt=\"form locker scheduling settings\" width=\"562\" height=\"486\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-scheduling-settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-scheduling-settings-300x260.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Start Date and Start Time:</strong> when the form will automatically open for submission on your site.</li>\n<li><strong>End Date and End Time:</strong> when the form will automatically close to site visitors.</li>\n<li><strong>Closed Message:</strong> the message that will display to site visitors who try to submit a closed form on your website.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If you want, you can always leave the Start or End fields empty, only scheduling an opening or closing date for your siteâs forms.</p>\n<p>Hereâs an example of how our party invitation RSVP form looks when form scheduling is enable and configured:</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-293948\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-scheduling-example.png\" alt=\"form locker scheduling example\" width=\"562\" height=\"497\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-scheduling-example.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-scheduling-example-300x265.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<p>And there you have it! You now know how to enable WordPress form scheduling for your siteâs forms so you can dictate how long your forms will be open for submission.</p>\n<p>If you want to learn about protecting your WordPress forms from spam submissions, be sure to check out our <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-build-spam-free-wordpress-contact-forms-the-ultimate-guide/\">guide to creating spam-free forms</a> on your website so you can <a href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/wordpress-security/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">keep your website secure</a>. In addition, check out how the Form Locker addon helps add an extra layer of protection to your forms by <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-password-protect-wordpress-forms-step-by-step/\">password protecting them</a>.</p>\n<p>So, what are you waiting for? Get started with the most powerful <a href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WordPress forms plugin</a> today.</p>\n<p>And donât forget, if you like this article, then please follow us on <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/wpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> and <a href=\"http://twitter.com/easywpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-enable-wordpress-form-scheduling-step-by-step/\">How to Enable WordPress Form Scheduling (Step by Step)</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:78:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-enable-wordpress-form-scheduling-step-by-step/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:7;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:54:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:47:\"How to Create a File Upload Widget in WordPress\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:68:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-file-upload-widget-in-wordpress/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:76:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-file-upload-widget-in-wordpress/#respond\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Mon, 15 Oct 2018 12:00:20 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:5:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:19:\"WordPress Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:11:\"form widget\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:21:\"wordpress widget form\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:11:\"file upload\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"widget\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:29:\"https://wpforms.com/?p=121041\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:568:\"<p>Are you looking for a way to allow your website visitors to send you files directly through your website? If you have a website that accepts user-submitted content or forms that require a file be uploaded, such as a job application form, having a file upload widget in your sidebar will definitely come in handy. [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-file-upload-widget-in-wordpress/\">How to Create a File Upload Widget in WordPress</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"Lindsay Liedke\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14612:\"<p>Are you looking for a way to allow your website visitors to send you files directly through your website? If you have a website that accepts user-submitted content or forms that require a file be uploaded, such as a job application form, having a file upload widget in your sidebar will definitely come in handy.</p>\n<p>In this article, weâll show you how to create a file upload widget in WordPress using WPForms.</p>\n<h3>Why Create a File Upload Widget?</h3>\n<p>The main reason to have a file upload widget in your sidebar is to make uploading files much easier for your users. This way, they don&#8217;t have to load a separate page to view your form or send files as email attachments.</p>\n<p>This is especially useful if youâre managing a website that involves user uploads, such as a graphic design blog that features freebies from designers, or a web design blog that showcases WordPress themes developed by your site visitors.</p>\n<p>Having a file upload widget on your sidebar will allow users to quickly upload their files for your review.</p>\n<p>You can also use a file upload widget to <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-get-more-guest-post-submissions-on-your-wordpress-blog/\">accept guest post submissions</a> or job applications. And this is just the beginning.</p>\n<p>Now, letâs see how to create a file upload form and add it to your websiteâs sidebar as a widget.</p>\n<h3>Step 1: Create A File Upload Form in WordPress</h3>\n<p>Before creating a file upload widget, you&#8217;ll need to <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-file-upload-form-in-wordpress/\">create a file upload form</a>.</p>\n<p>Follow the instructions in the video to create a file upload form with basic contact form fields like Name, Email, and Message.</p>\n<p><iframe width=\"600\" height=\"338\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/zPVHHX99N_g?feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"autoplay; encrypted-media\" allowfullscreen></iframe></p>\n<p>If you prefer reading, follow the steps below to create a unique file upload form. For the sake of this tutorial, weâll show you how to create an upload form for a website theme marketplace or a blog.</p>\n<p>The first thing youâll need to do is install and activate the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/pricing/\">WPForms plugin</a>. For more details, see this step by step guide on <a title=\"Step by step guide on How to Install a WordPress Plugin\" href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/step-by-step-guide-to-install-a-wordpress-plugin-for-beginners/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">how to install a plugin in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>Next, go to <strong>WPForms Â» Add New</strong> and choose the <strong>Blank Form</strong> template.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-293715\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/blank-form-template.png\" alt=\"blank form template\" width=\"562\" height=\"357\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/blank-form-template.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/blank-form-template-300x191.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>This will give you a blank form so you can add any form fields to the form you want, including the <strong>File Upload</strong> form field so users can upload their files.</p>\n<p>Alternatively, you can use the WPForms <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/form-templates-pack-addon/\">Form Templates Pack addon</a>, so you can use the <strong>File Upload Form</strong> template.</p>\n<p>To do this, go to <strong>WPForms</strong> Â» <strong>Addon</strong> and find the one labeled <strong>Form Templates Pack addon</strong>.</p>\n<p>Click <strong>Install Addon</strong> and then <strong>Activate</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-291194\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-templates-pack-addon.png\" alt=\"form templates pack addon\" width=\"562\" height=\"193\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-templates-pack-addon.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-templates-pack-addon-300x103.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Now youâll need to create a new form.</p>\n<p>To do this, go to <strong>WPForms</strong> Â» <strong>Add New</strong>, name your form, and choose the <strong>File Upload Form</strong> template.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-293290\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/file-upload-form-template.png\" alt=\"file upload form template\" width=\"562\" height=\"241\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/file-upload-form-template.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/file-upload-form-template-300x129.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>WPForms will create a form for you.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-293291\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/file-upload-form.png\" alt=\"file upload form\" width=\"562\" height=\"478\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/file-upload-form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/file-upload-form-300x255.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>If you want, you can also choose the Job Application Form template and <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-job-application-form-in-wordpress/\">create a job application form</a> that requires file uploads as well.</p>\n<h3>Step 2: Customize Your File Upload Form</h3>\n<p>WPForms makes customizing forms easy to do.</p>\n<p>You can add additional form fields to your file upload form by dragging them from the left hand panel to the right hand panel. Then, to make changes just click on the form field.</p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-124033\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/add-file-upload-field.gif\" alt=\"add file upload field\" width=\"570\" height=\"339\" /></p>\n<p>You can add many form fields to your form to make it more effective and suit your individual needs. For example, you can add checkboxes, dropdown menus, and even <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/stripe-addon/\">add credit card processing</a> to accept payments.</p>\n<p>If you need help with accepting payments on you forms, check out this article on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-require-payment-on-a-wordpress-file-upload-form/\">how to require payment on a WordPress file upload form</a>.</p>\n<p>Itâs important you customize the <strong>File Upload</strong> field to make sure site visitors can upload the files they need to when submitting your form.</p>\n<p>To do this, click on the <strong>File Upload</strong> field and do the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Change the label so people know what to upload</li>\n<li>Add a description with instructions if needed</li>\n<li>Specify the types of file extensions youâll allow people to upload</li>\n<li>Enter a maximum file size if you want to restrict the size to be smaller than the default of 128MB</li>\n<li>Click the <strong>Required</strong> checkbox if everyone submitting a form must upload a file</li>\n</ul>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-293289\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/customize-file-upload-form-field.png\" alt=\"customize file upload form field\" width=\"562\" height=\"333\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/customize-file-upload-form-field.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/customize-file-upload-form-field-300x178.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>The file upload form field will support the following file types:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Images</strong> such as .png, .gif, and .jpg</li>\n<li><strong>Documents</strong> like .doc, .xls, .ppt, and .pdf</li>\n<li><strong>Audio</strong> like .wav, .mp3, and .mp4</li>\n<li><strong>Video</strong> such as .mpg, .mov, and .wmv</li>\n</ul>\n<p>For our example, youâll need to check out our documentation on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-allow-additional-file-upload-types/\">how to allow additional files types</a> since WordPress will not allow code files such as .css, .js, or .json.</p>\n<p>Lastly, under the <strong>Advanced Options</strong> section, you can click the checkbox labeled <strong>Store file in WordPress Media Library</strong> for easy access to the files users upload.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-235139\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Store-Files-in-Media-Library.png\" alt=\"Store Files in Media Library\" width=\"562\" height=\"210\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Store-Files-in-Media-Library.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Store-Files-in-Media-Library-300x112.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>When youâre done customizing your form, click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Step 3: Configure Your File Upload Form Settings</h3>\n<p>There are many settings to configure once youâve customized your form to look the way you want it to.</p>\n<p><strong>General Settings</strong><br />\nTo start, go to <strong>Settings</strong> Â» <strong>General</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-246850\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-General-Settings.png\" alt=\"WPForms General Settings\" width=\"562\" height=\"443\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-General-Settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-General-Settings-300x236.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Here you can change things like your formâs name, description, and submit button copy.</p>\n<p>You can also <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-build-spam-free-wordpress-contact-forms-the-ultimate-guide/\">enable additional spam prevention features</a> to <a href=\"https://www.wpbeginner.com/wordpress-security/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">keep your website secure</a> from unwanted form submissions.</p>\n<p><strong>Form Notifications</strong><br />\nNotifications are a great way to send an email whenever a form is submitted on your website.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-246852\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-Notifications-Settings.png\" alt=\"WPForms Notifications Settings\" width=\"562\" height=\"228\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-Notifications-Settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-Notifications-Settings-300x122.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>In fact, unless you disable this feature, whenever someone submits a file upload form on your site, youâll get a notification about it.</p>\n<p>For help with this step, check out our documentation on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/setup-form-notification-wpforms/\">how to set up form notifications in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>If you need to send more than one notification, for example to yourself, your head developer, and your site visitor, check out our step by step tutorial on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-multiple-form-notifications-in-wordpress-forms/\">how to send multiple form notifications in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p><strong>Form Confirmations</strong><br />\nForm confirmations are messages that display to site visitors once they submit a file upload form on your website. They let people know that their form has been processed and offer you the chance to let them know what the next steps are.</p>\n<p>WPForms has three confirmation types:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Message. </strong>A simple message that displays once someone submits a form on your website thanking them and letting them know what the next steps are.</li>\n<li><strong>Show Page.</strong> Redirect users to another page on your website, such as a thank you page.</li>\n<li><strong>Go to URL (Redirect).</strong> Send site visitors to a different website.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>If you want to display different confirmations to site visitors based on the type of file they upload, be sure to read up on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-create-conditional-form-confirmations/\">how to create conditional form confirmations</a>.</p>\n<p>Click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Step 4: Create a File Upload Form Widget in WordPress</h3>\n<p>Now letâs see how to turn the file upload form you just created into a widget and display it on your siteâs sidebar.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 1:</strong> Go to <strong>Appearance Â» Widgets</strong> in your WordPress dashboard.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 2: </strong>Find the <strong>WPForms</strong> widget and drag it onto your preferred sidebar. Where you can place the WPForms widget will depend on the WordPress theme you use and what widget sections are available on your website.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-293292\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/wpforms-widget.png\" alt=\"wpforms widget\" width=\"562\" height=\"311\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/wpforms-widget.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/wpforms-widget-300x166.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p><strong>Step 3: </strong>Select the <strong>file upload form</strong> youâve just created from the forms list and click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<p>Go to your website and see your file upload form on your website sidebar.</p>\n<p>And there you have it! You now know how to create a file upload form widget in WordPress and add it to your websiteâs sidebar.</p>\n<p>If you want to add a file upload form to other unique places on your website, check out this tutorial on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-add-a-contact-form-to-your-wordpress-footer/\">how to add a form to your WordPress footer</a>. And if you want to, you can also check out this article on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-wordpress-contact-form-multiple-file-upload/\">creating WordPress forms with multiple file uploads</a> so site visitors donât have to submit more than one form at a time.</p>\n<p>So, what are you waiting for? Get started with the most powerful <a href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WordPress forms plugin</a> today.</p>\n<p>And donât forget, if you like this article, then please follow us on <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/wpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> and <a href=\"http://twitter.com/easywpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-file-upload-widget-in-wordpress/\">How to Create a File Upload Widget in WordPress</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:73:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-file-upload-widget-in-wordpress/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:8;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:57:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:57:\"How to Create a Customer Cancellation Survey in WordPress\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:78:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-customer-cancellation-survey-in-wordpress/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:86:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-customer-cancellation-survey-in-wordpress/#respond\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Thu, 11 Oct 2018 12:00:34 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:6:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:19:\"WordPress Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"form templates\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:19:\"form templates pack\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:12:\"likert scale\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:11:\"survey form\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:5;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"NPS form field\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:29:\"https://wpforms.com/?p=111115\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:603:\"<p>Want to find out why your customers canceled their subscription with you? With our form templates pack, itâs so easy to create a cancellation survey form in WordPress. Just choose the cancellation survey template and start customizing it using the drag and drop form builder. In this article, weâll show you how to create a [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-customer-cancellation-survey-in-wordpress/\">How to Create a Customer Cancellation Survey in WordPress</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"Lindsay Liedke\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:16564:\"<p>Want to find out why your customers canceled their subscription with you? With our form templates pack, itâs so easy to create a cancellation survey form in WordPress. Just choose the cancellation survey template and start customizing it using the drag and drop form builder.</p>\n<p>In this article, weâll show you how to create a customer cancellation survey in just a few clicks.</p>\n<h3>Why Create a Customer Cancellation Survey?</h3>\n<p>With a Customer Cancellation Survey form, you can ask all the right questions to your former clients in an easy way. You can tell them how sorry you are to see them go and identify the reasons they left you.</p>\n<p>The insights from this survey will help you create a strategy to retain your current customers.</p>\n<h3>Step 1: Create a Customer Cancellation Survey Form in WordPress</h3>\n<p>The first thing youâll need to do is install and activate the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/pricing/\">WPForms plugin</a>. For more details, see this step by step guide on <a title=\"Step by step guide on How to Install a WordPress Plugin\" href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/step-by-step-guide-to-install-a-wordpress-plugin-for-beginners/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">how to install a plugin in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>Next, youâll need to install and activate the <a href=\" https://wpforms.com/addons/form-templates-pack-addon/\">Form Templates Pack addon</a>.</p>\n<p>To do this, go to <strong>WPForms</strong> Â» <strong>Addon</strong> and find the one labeled <strong>Form Templates Pack addon</strong>.</p>\n<p>Click <strong>Install Addon</strong> and then <strong>Activate</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-291194\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-templates-pack-addon.png\" alt=\"form templates pack addon\" width=\"562\" height=\"193\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-templates-pack-addon.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-templates-pack-addon-300x103.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Now youâll need to create a new form.</p>\n<p>To do this, go to <strong>WPForms</strong> Â» <strong>Add New</strong>, name your form, and choose the <strong>Cancellation Survey Form</strong> template.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-291191\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/cancellation-form-template.png\" alt=\"cancellation form template\" width=\"562\" height=\"488\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/cancellation-form-template.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/cancellation-form-template-300x260.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>WPForms will create a form for you.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-291193\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/customer-cancellation-survey-form.png\" alt=\"customer cancellation survey form\" width=\"562\" height=\"345\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/customer-cancellation-survey-form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/customer-cancellation-survey-form-300x184.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>This form comes with several pre-written questions to ask those that are cancelling services with you. This includes multiple choice questions as well as open-ended paragraph text form fields where people can express their opinions and give you insight into how you might do things differently next time.</p>\n<p>You can add additional fields to your form by dragging them from the left hand panel to the right hand panel.</p>\n<p>Then, click on the field to make any changes. You can also click on a form field and drag it to rearrange the order on your cancellation survey form.</p>\n<h3>Step 2: Customize the Survey Form Fields</h3>\n<p>You can easily add new <strong>Multiple Choice</strong> fields to your form to ask people more questions about why theyâre cancelling with you.</p>\n<p>That said, letâs take a look at some of the other form fields you might want to add to your cancellation survey form to get the most information from previous customers as possible:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Net Promoter Score:</strong> the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-net-promoter-score-nps-survey-in-wordpress/\">Net Promoter Score (NPS) form field</a> is great for finding out whether past customers would recommend your company to a family or friend. After all, just because someone is cancelling with you doesnât mean they arenât satisfied. Adding this field to your form allows you to generate a Net Promoter Score for your business. If itâs high, this can serve as <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/brilliant-examples-of-social-proof-for-your-sites-forms/\">social proof to get new site visitors to sign up with you</a>.</li>\n<li><strong>Likert Scale:</strong> the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/beginners-guide-what-is-a-likert-scale-and-how-to-use-it/\">Likert Scale form field</a> is used to find out how people feel about something. For instance, on your cancellation survey form you can ask people about your products, services, or customer service to see whether any of those things played into why they are cancelling. Look here for some <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/sample-likert-scale-questions-for-wordpress-survey-forms/\">helpful Likert Scale questions</a> to add to your survey form.</li>\n<li><strong>Rating:</strong> Another great way to gauge how people felt about your business is to <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-add-user-ratings-to-your-wordpress-forms-step-by-step/\">add a rating form field to your survey form</a>. This way, no matter how your past customer feels, youâll know whether youâre doing a good job or not. Plus, you can <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-easily-enable-conditional-logic-for-user-ratings-in-wordpress/\">enable conditional logic on your rating field</a> so that if someone rates your business low, you can ask them to explain why.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Customizing your cancellation survey form is easy to do when you use WPForms.</p>\n<p>If you personalize your forms, youâll find that getting information from customers, disgruntled or not, also becomes a lot easier so you can make the necessary changes in the future to prevent people from cancelling with you.</p>\n<h3>Step 3: Configure Your Cancellation Formâs Settings</h3>\n<p>There are many settings to configure once youâve customized your form to look the way you want it to.</p>\n<p><strong>General Settings</strong><br />\nTo start, go to <strong>Settings</strong> Â» <strong>General</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-246850\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-General-Settings.png\" alt=\"WPForms General Settings\" width=\"562\" height=\"443\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-General-Settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-General-Settings-300x236.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Here you can change things like your formâs name, description, and submit button copy.</p>\n<p>You can also <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-build-spam-free-wordpress-contact-forms-the-ultimate-guide/\">enable additional spam prevention features</a> to <a href=\"https://www.wpbeginner.com/wordpress-security/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">keep your website secure</a> from unwanted form submissions.</p>\n<p><strong>Form Notifications</strong><br />\nNotifications are a great way to send an email whenever an order is submitted on your website.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-246852\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-Notifications-Settings.png\" alt=\"WPForms Notifications Settings\" width=\"562\" height=\"228\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-Notifications-Settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-Notifications-Settings-300x122.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>In fact, unless you disable this feature, whenever someone submits a cancellation form on your site, youâll get a notification about it.</p>\n<p>For help with this step, check out our documentation on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/setup-form-notification-wpforms/\">how to set up form notifications in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>If you need to send more than one notification, for example to yourself, the customer service team, and your previous customer, check out our step by step tutorial on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-multiple-form-notifications-in-wordpress-forms/\">how to send multiple form notifications in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p><strong>Form Confirmations</strong><br />\nForm confirmations are messages that display to site visitors once they submit a form on your website.</p>\n<p>WPForms has three confirmation types:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Message. </strong>A simple message that displays once someone submits a form on your website thanking them and letting them know what the next steps are.</li>\n<li><strong>Show Page.</strong> Redirect users to another page on your website, such as a thank you page.</li>\n<li><strong>Go to URL (Redirect).</strong> Send site visitors to a different website.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>If you want to display different confirmations to site visitors based on their survey answers, be sure to read up on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-create-conditional-form-confirmations/\">how to create conditional form confirmations</a>.</p>\n<h3>Step 4: Enable Survey Reporting</h3>\n<p>In order to receive the results of your survey form as site visitors fill it out, you need to enable survey reporting.</p>\n<p>To do this, go to <strong>Settings</strong> Â» <strong> Surveys and Polls</strong>. Then, click on the <strong>Enable Survey Reporting</strong> checkbox. This will enable survey reporting sitewide.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-224833\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Enable-Survey-Reporting.png\" alt=\"Enable Survey Reporting\" width=\"562\" height=\"262\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Enable-Survey-Reporting.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Enable-Survey-Reporting-300x140.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>In other words, WPForms will collect survey results for any of the following form fields <strong>on all your siteâs forms</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Single Line Text</li>\n<li>Paragraph Text</li>\n<li>Dropdown</li>\n<li>Checkboxes</li>\n<li>Multiple Choice</li>\n<li>Rating</li>\n<li>Likert Scale</li>\n<li>Net Promoter Score</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If you donât want to collect survey results for every form on your website, unclick the <strong>Enable Survey Reporting</strong> checkbox under <strong>Settings</strong>.</p>\n<p>Next, return to your form in the Form Editor, click on the field you want to enable reporting for, and under the <strong>Advanced Options</strong> section, check the <strong>Enable Survey Reporting</strong> box. Now only survey results on that particular form field will be collected.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-224842\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Enable-Survey-Reporting-in-Form-Editor.png\" alt=\"Enable Survey Reporting in Form Editor\" width=\"562\" height=\"338\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Enable-Survey-Reporting-in-Form-Editor.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Enable-Survey-Reporting-in-Form-Editor-300x180.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Do this for each form field you want to collect results for.</p>\n<h3>Step 5: Add Your Customer Cancellation Form to Your Website</h3>\n<p>After youâve created your cancellation survey form, and all the settings are set, you need to add it to your website.</p>\n<p>WPForms allows you to add your forms to many locations on your website, including your blog posts, pages, and even <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-add-a-contact-form-in-wordpress-sidebar-widget/\">sidebar widgets</a>.</p>\n<p>Letâs take a look at the most common post/page embed option.</p>\n<p>To start, create a new post or page in WordPress and then click on the <strong>Add Form</strong> button.</p>\n<p>Next, select your cancellation form from the modal popup and click <strong>Add Form</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-291190\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/add-cancellation-form.png\" alt=\"add cancellation form\" width=\"562\" height=\"278\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/add-cancellation-form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/add-cancellation-form-300x148.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Then, publish your post or page so your survey form will appear on your website.</p>\n<h3>Step 6: Generate Survey Reports</h3>\n<p>One people start filling out your cancellation survey form, you can begin to analyze the data thatâs collected.</p>\n<p>To generate a survey report, go to <strong>WPForms</strong> Â» <strong>All Forms</strong> and hover over your survey form to display the options. Then, click on <strong>Survey Results</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-291192\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/cancellation-survey-form-report.png\" alt=\"cancellation survey form report\" width=\"562\" height=\"261\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/cancellation-survey-form-report.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/cancellation-survey-form-report-300x139.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Youâll see survey results for each form field that has survey reporting enabled on it.</p>\n<p>For instance, here is what the results for the first question on your survey form might look like:</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-291195\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/survey-results.png\" alt=\"survey results\" width=\"562\" height=\"315\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/survey-results.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/survey-results-300x168.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<h3>Sample Customer Exit Survey Questions</h3>\n<p>The default questions in the cancellation survey template are:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>How long had you been using the subscription / service?</li>\n<li>How often did you use the subscription / service?</li>\n<li>Overall, how satisfied were you with the subscription / service?</li>\n<li>What was the primary reason for canceling your subscription / service?</li>\n<li>Would you use the product / service in the future?</li>\n<li>Would you recommend our product / service to colleagues or contacts within your industry?</li>\n<li>What could we do to improve our subscription / service?</li>\n</ul>\n<p>To get the most responses, we recommend keeping your survey as short as possible. In other words, choose your questions wisely.</p>\n<p>Here are a few other revealing cancellation questions you might consider asking:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Did we meet your expectations?</li>\n<li>Is there anything we could have done differently?</li>\n<li>What was the greatest benefit you got from the product / service?</li>\n<li>Has the support team treated you with the attention and courteousness you expected?</li>\n<li>Was the billing clear?</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Asking these hard-hitting questions will get you the information needed to make data-driven decisions to grow your business into a success.</p>\n<p>And there you have it! You now know how to create a customer cancellation survey form in WordPress.</p>\n<p>If you enjoyed this article, you might also want to read up on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-increase-survey-response-rates-and-build-your-business/\">how to increase survey response rates</a> so you can continue to build your business.</p>\n<p>So, what are you waiting for? Get started with the most powerful <a href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WordPress forms plugin</a> today.</p>\n<p>And donât forget, if you like this article, then please follow us on <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/wpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> and <a href=\"http://twitter.com/easywpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-customer-cancellation-survey-in-wordpress/\">How to Create a Customer Cancellation Survey in WordPress</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:83:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-customer-cancellation-survey-in-wordpress/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:9;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:54:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:54:\"How to Password Protect WordPress Forms (Step by Step)\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:73:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-password-protect-wordpress-forms-step-by-step/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:81:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-password-protect-wordpress-forms-step-by-step/#respond\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Wed, 10 Oct 2018 12:00:47 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:5:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:19:\"WordPress Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:16:\"post submissions\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:25:\"frontend post submissions\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:16:\"password protect\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:17:\"form locker addon\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:28:\"https://wpforms.com/?p=67806\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:573:\"<p>Do you want to prevent unwanted form submissions? The best way to do this is to make your WordPress form password protected. In this article, weâll show you two ways to password protect WordPress forms. Here are some quick links so you can check out which method you want to use to password protect your [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-password-protect-wordpress-forms-step-by-step/\">How to Password Protect WordPress Forms (Step by Step)</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"Lindsay Liedke\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13573:\"<p>Do you want to prevent unwanted form submissions? The best way to do this is to make your WordPress form password protected.</p>\n<p>In this article, weâll show you two ways to password protect WordPress forms.</p>\n<p>Here are some quick links so you can check out which method you want to use to password protect your WordPress forms:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#in-editor\">How to Password Protect Your Form in the WordPress Editor</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#with-addon\">How to Password Protect Your Form Using the Form Locker Addon</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Why Password Protect WordPress Forms?</h3>\n<p>Password protecting your WordPress forms prevent unwanted form submissions. This way you can ensure that only authorized people can access your WordPress forms.</p>\n<p>Letâs take a look at a possible use case of protecting your form with a password.</p>\n<p>Imagine that youâre accepting guest post submissions on your blog using the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/post-submissions-addon/\">Post Submissions addon</a>. The Post Submissions addon allows you to accept user generated content like a blog post or any other form of content on the front-end of your site without allowing users to log into your admin area.</p>\n<p>If you allow everyone to access your post submissions form, chances are you&#8217;ll receive a lot of low-quality articles. By password protecting such a form, you can prevent unwanted guest post submissions. Thatâs because only people with the password will be able to submit their content.</p>\n<p>Doing this prevents you from wasting your time reviewing content youâll never use.</p>\n<p>Now let&#8217;s take a look at how to password protect your forms in the WordPress Editor.</p>\n<h3 id=\"in-editor\">How to Password Protect Your Form in the WordPress Editor</h3>\n<p><strong>Step 1: Create a New Form in WordPress</strong><br />\nThe first thing youâll need to do is install and activate the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/pricing/\">WPForms plugin</a>. For more details, see this step by step guide on <a title=\"Step by step guide on How to Install a WordPress Plugin\" href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/step-by-step-guide-to-install-a-wordpress-plugin-for-beginners/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">how to install a plugin in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>Next, youâll need to create a new form. Using our post submission form example, see our tutorial on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-allow-users-to-submit-blog-posts-on-your-wordpress-site/\">how to create a post submission form</a>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-235138\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Final-Blog-Post-Submission-Form.png\" alt=\"Final Blog Post Submission Form\" width=\"562\" height=\"906\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Final-Blog-Post-Submission-Form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Final-Blog-Post-Submission-Form-186x300.png 186w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Once youâve customized your form to meet your needs, add it to a post or page on your website. For help with this step, check out this tutorial on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-add-a-contact-form-in-your-wordpress-post-content/\">how to add a form to your WordPress content</a>.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 2: Password Protect Your Form</strong><br />\nOnce your form is created, and published on a WordPress post or page, go to the WordPress dashboard and access the place your form has been published.</p>\n<p>In the Publish box, found in the WordPress Editor, edit the visibility of the page by clicking <strong>Edit</strong> and choosing the option <strong>Password protected</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-67829\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/passwordprotect.png\" alt=\"password protect wordpress forms\" width=\"520\" height=\"368\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/passwordprotect.png 520w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/passwordprotect-300x212.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 520px) 100vw, 520px\" /></p>\n<p>In the <strong>Password</strong> field, enter the password you want to set. Then click <strong>OK</strong>, and update the post.</p>\n<p>Now you can give the people you want filling out your form on your website, and posting content, the password so they can view your protected page and submit their form. And remember, you can do this for any WordPress form you create on your website.</p>\n<p>Now letâs take a look at how to use the WPForms Form Locker addon to password protect your WordPress forms.</p>\n<h3 id=\"with-addon\">How to Password Protect Your Form Using the Form Locker Addon</h3>\n<p><strong>Step 1: Create a New Form in WordPress</strong><br />\nThe first thing youâll need to do is install and activate the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/pricing/\">WPForms plugin</a>. For more details, see this step by step guide on <a title=\"Step by step guide on How to Install a WordPress Plugin\" href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/step-by-step-guide-to-install-a-wordpress-plugin-for-beginners/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">how to install a plugin in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>Next, go to <strong>WPForms Â» Addons</strong> and find the <strong>Form Locker Addon</strong>.</p>\n<p>Install and activate the Form Locker addon.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-290577\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-addon.png\" alt=\"form locker addon\" width=\"562\" height=\"200\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-addon.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-addon-300x107.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Once your WPForms Form Locker addon is active, youâll need to create a new form. Using our post submission form example, see our tutorial on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-allow-users-to-submit-blog-posts-on-your-wordpress-site/\">how to create a post submission form</a>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-235138\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Final-Blog-Post-Submission-Form.png\" alt=\"Final Blog Post Submission Form\" width=\"562\" height=\"906\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Final-Blog-Post-Submission-Form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Final-Blog-Post-Submission-Form-186x300.png 186w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>If you want to create a different type of form on your website, and protect it with a password, check out the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-install-and-use-the-form-templates-pack-addon/\">Form Templates Pack addon</a> and choose from over 100 pre-designed templates.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 2: Configure Form Locker Settings</strong><br />\nAfter your form is customized to meet your needs, go to <strong>Settings</strong> Â» <strong>Form Locker</strong> in the Form Editor.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-290580\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-settings.png\" alt=\"form locker settings\" width=\"562\" height=\"359\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-settings-300x192.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>To password protect your newly created form, select the <strong>Enable password protection</strong> checkbox under the <strong>Password</strong> section.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-290578\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-password-protection.png\" alt=\"form locker password protection\" width=\"562\" height=\"333\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-password-protection.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-locker-password-protection-300x178.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>When you do this, a new screen will appear where you can configure the password protection settings.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-290579\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/password-settings.png\" alt=\"password settings\" width=\"562\" height=\"495\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/password-settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/password-settings-300x264.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>These settings include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Password:</strong> this is the password people will be required to enter before submitting a form on your website.</li>\n<li><strong>Display Message:</strong> this is the message that will appear above the Password field so people know that your form is protected and requires a password to submit.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<p>This is what your password protected WordPress form will look like on the front-end of your site:</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-290576\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/final-password-protected-form.png\" alt=\"final password protected form\" width=\"562\" height=\"235\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/final-password-protected-form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/final-password-protected-form-300x125.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Once the correct password is entered, your WordPress form will appear for your site visitor to fill out and submit.</p>\n<p>The great thing about this option is that you don&#8217;t have to protect the entire page with a password, like you do when you password protect forms using the WordPress Editor.</p>\n<p>Instead, people can still view the content, such as a blog post, without having to have a password. Your site visitors will only need the password if they want to submit the form. This improves the user experience and makes you more transparent.</p>\n<p>After all, people don&#8217;t want to feel like you are hiding content from them.</p>\n<h3>How to Hide the Page From Search Engines</h3>\n<p>To keep away unwanted users from accessing the page youâve added a password protected form to in search results, you might also want to <a href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/wordpress-seo/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">hide the page from search engines</a>.</p>\n<p>To do this, find your <a href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/glossary/robots-txt/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">robots.txt</a> file and add the following code to it. Make sure to replace <strong>/your-page/</strong> with your page URL in the code.</p>\n<pre class=\"brush: xml; title: ; notranslate\">\nUser-agent: *\nDisallow: /your-page/\n</pre>\n<p>For more details, you can read <a href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/wp-tutorials/how-to-hide-a-wordpress-page-from-google/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">how to hide a page from search engines</a>.</p>\n<h3>How to Hide Your Post From Your Homepage</h3>\n<p>If you&#8217;re embedding the password protected form in a blog post, you might also want to hide that post from appearing on your homepage, while still allowing others to view it if they have the URL.</p>\n<p>To hide the post from your homepage, you can use the plugin <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/wp-hide-post/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">WP Hide Post</a>. After activating the plugin, go to the post edit screen where you&#8217;ll find a new meta box labeled âPost Visibilityâ.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-67833\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/post-visibility.png\" alt=\"post visibility\" width=\"520\" height=\"249\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/post-visibility.png 520w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/post-visibility-300x144.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 520px) 100vw, 520px\" /></p>\n<p>Click the checkbox near <strong>Hide on the front page</strong>. Now, only people with the exact URL to your webpage will be able to see your form. Otherwise, when someone visits your website, they will not see the post with the form on your homepage.</p>\n<p>And there you have it! You now know how to password protect WordPress forms in two very easy ways.</p>\n<p>If you&#8217;re accepting guest posts on your blog, you can read these <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-get-more-guest-post-submissions-on-your-wordpress-blog/\">4 tactics to attract more guest article submissions</a>. And if youâre interested in learning about other ways to prevent unwanted form submissions, check out this detailed guide to <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-build-spam-free-wordpress-contact-forms-the-ultimate-guide/\">building spam-free WordPress contact forms</a>.</p>\n<p>And if you still aren&#8217;t sure WPForms is for you, <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/user-reviews/\">check out what others have to say</a> about the most beginner friendly contact form builder on the market today.</p>\n<p>So, what are you waiting for? Get started with the most powerful <a href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WordPress forms plugin</a> today.</p>\n<p>And donât forget, if you like this article, then please follow us on <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/wpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> and <a href=\"http://twitter.com/easywpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-password-protect-wordpress-forms-step-by-step/\">How to Password Protect WordPress Forms (Step by Step)</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:78:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-password-protect-wordpress-forms-step-by-step/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}}}s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:1:{s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:3:{s:4:\"href\";s:25:\"https://wpforms.com/feed/\";s:3:\"rel\";s:4:\"self\";s:4:\"type\";s:19:\"application/rss+xml\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:44:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/syndication/\";a:2:{s:12:\"updatePeriod\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"hourly\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:15:\"updateFrequency\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}}}}}}}}s:4:\"type\";i:128;s:7:\"headers\";O:42:\"Requests_Utility_CaseInsensitiveDictionary\":